\h 2 Samuel
\id 2SA
\c 1
\p
\v 1 And it happened after the death of Saul, when David had returned from killing Amalek, and David had stayed two days in Ziklag,
\v 2 it happened on the third day that, behold, a man came out of the camp from Saul, with his clothes torn, and earth on his head. And so it was, when he came to David, that he fell on his face to the earth, and did obeisance.
\v 3 And David said to him, "Where have you come from?" And he said to him, "I have escaped out of the camp of Israel."
\v 4 And David said to him, "How did the matter go? Please tell me." And he answered, "The people have fled from the battle, and many of the people also have fallen, and Saul and Jonathan his son are dead also."
\v 5 And David said to the young man who told it to him, "How do you know that Saul and Jonathan his son are dead?"
\v 6 And the young man who told it to him said, "It happened that I happened to be on Mount Gilboa, and behold, Saul was leaning on his spear, and, behold, the chariots and the horsemen followed hard after him.
\v 7 And when he looked behind him, he saw me, and called to me. And I answered, 'Here I am.'
\v 8 And he said to me, 'Who are you?' And I answered him, 'I am an Amalekite.'
\v 9 And he said to me, 'Please stand beside me and kill me, for anguish has taken hold of me, because my soul is still in me.'
\v 10 And I stood beside him, and killed him, because I was sure that he could not live after he had fallen. And I took the crown that was on his head, and the bracelet that was on his arm, and have brought them here to my lord."
\p
\v 11 Then David took hold of his clothes and tore them, and all the men who were with him did the same.
\v 12 And they mourned, and wept, and fasted until evening, for Saul, and for Jonathan his son, and for the people of the \nd Lord\nd*, and for the house of Israel, because they had fallen by the sword.
\v 13 And David said to the young man who told it to him, "Where do you come from?" And he answered, "I am the son of a sojourner, an Amalekite."
\v 14 And David said to him, "Why were you not afraid to put forth your hand to destroy the \nd Lord\nd*'s anointed one?"
\v 15 And David called one of the young men, and said, "Go near, and fall on him." And he struck him, and threw him to the ground.
\v 16 And David said to him, "Your blood is on your head, for your mouth has given witness against you, saying, 'I have killed the \nd Lord\nd*'s anointed one.'"
\p
\v 17 And David lamented with this lamentation over Saul and over Jonathan his son,
\v 18 and he told them to teach it to the sons of Israel and Judah. Behold, it is written in the book of Jashar. And he said:
\p
\v 19 Take your stand, O Israel, over your dead who are slain.
\p
How the mighty ones have fallen!
\p
\v 20 Tell it not in Gath,
\p
Announce it not in the streets of Ashkelon,
\p
Lest the daughters of the Philistines rejoice,
\p
Lest the daughters of the uncircumcised triumph.
\p
\v 21 You mountains of Gilboa, Let it not fall upon you,
\p
And let there be no dew nor rain upon your ridges, O mountains of death,
\p
For there the shield of the mighty was vilely cast away,
\p
The shield of Saul, not anointed with oil.
\p
\v 22 From the blood of the slain, from the fat of the mighty,
\p
The bow of Jonathan turned not back,
\p
And the sword of Saul returned not empty.
\p
\v 23 Saul and Jonathan were lovely and pleasant.
\p
They were not separated in their life,
\p
And in their death they were not divided.
\p
They were swifter than eagles,
\p
They were stronger than lions.
\p
\v 24 Weep over Saul, O daughters of Israel,
\p
Who clothed you delicately in scarlet,
\p
Who put ornaments of gold on your clothing.
\p
\v 25 How are the mighty fallen in the midst of the battle!
\p
Jonathan is slain upon death.
\p
\v 26 I am distressed for you, my brother Jonathan,
\p
Very pleasant have you been to me,
\p
Your love fell on me like the love of the women.
\p
\v 27 How are the mighty fallen,
\p
And the precious articles have perished!
\c 2
\p
\v 1 And it happened after this, that David asked of the \nd Lord\nd*, saying, "Shall I go up into any of the cities of Judah?" And the \nd Lord\nd* said to him, "Go up." And David said, "Where shall I go up?" And he said, "To Hebron."
\v 2 And David went up to Hebron with his two wives, Ahinoam the Jezreelitess, and Abigail the wife of Nabal the Carmelite,
\v 3 and his men who were with him, every man with his household, and they lived in the cities of Hebron.
\v 4 And the men of Judah came and anointed David king over the house of Judah there.
\p
And they told David, saying, "The men of Jabesh-gilead were the ones who buried Saul."
\v 5 And David sent messengers to the men of Jabesh-gilead, and said to them, "You are blessed of the \nd Lord\nd*, in that you have shown this kindness to your lord, to Saul, and have buried him.
\v 6 And now may the \nd Lord\nd* show kindness and truth to you, and I also will do good to you because you have done this thing.
\v 7 And now let your hands be strong, and be sons of valour, for Saul your lord is dead, and the house of Judah have also anointed me king over them."
\p
\v 8 And Abiner the son of Ner was captain of Saul's host and he had taken Eshbaal the son of Saul, and brought him over to Mahanaim.
\v 9 And he made him king over the Gileadites, and over the Ashurites, and over Jezreel, and over Ephraim, and over Benjamin, and over all Israel.
\v 10 Eshbaal, Saul's son, was forty years old when he began to reign over Israel, and he reigned two years. But the house of Judah followed David.
\v 11 And the time that David was king in Hebron over the house of Judah was seven years and six months.
\p
\v 12 And Abiner the son of Ner and the servants of Eshbaal the son of Saul went out from Mahanaim to Gibeon.
\v 13 And Joab the son of Zeruiah and the servants of David went out and met them by the pool of Gibeon, and they sat, one on one side of the pool, and the other on the other side of the pool.
\v 14 And Abiner said to Joab, "Please let the young men rise and play before us." And Joab said, "Let them rise."
\v 15 Then they rose and went over by number: twelve of the Benjamites of Eshbaal the son of Saul, and twelve of the servants of David.
\v 16 And each caught his neighbour by the head, and \add thrust\add* his sword in his neighbour's side and they fell down together. And that place was called Helkath-hazodim\f + \fr 2:16 \ft That is, Field of plotters, as in the first part, 24:11.\f*, which is in Gibeon.
\p
\v 17 And the battle was very severe that day, and Abiner and the men of Israel were beaten before the servants of David.
\v 18 And the three sons of Zeruiah were there: Joab, and Abishai, and Asahel. And Asahel was as light of foot as a wild doe.
\v 19 And Asahel pursued Abiner, and in going he did not turn to the right hand nor to the left from following Abiner.
\v 20 Then Abiner looked behind him, and said, "Is it you, Asahel?" And he answered, "It is I."
\v 21 And Abiner said to him, "Turn aside to your right hand or to your left, and lay hold on one of the young men, and take his armour." And Asahel would not turn from following him.
\v 22 And again Abiner said to Asahel, "Turn from following me! Why should I strike you to the ground? How then should I hold up my face to Joab your brother? And how can these things be? Return to your brother Joab."
\v 23 And Asahel refused to turn aside; and Abiner struck him in the body with the foot of the spear, and the spear came out behind him, and he fell down there and died in the same place. And it happened, that whoever came to the place where Asahel fell down and died stood still.
\p
\v 24 And Joab and Abishai pursued Abiner, and the sun went down when they had come to the hill of Ammah that lies before Giah by the way of the wilderness of Gibeon.
\v 25 And the children of Benjamin gathered themselves together after Abiner, and became one band, and stood on the top of a hill.
\v 26 Then Abiner called to Joab, and said, "Shall the sword devour forever? Don't you know that the end will be bitter? How long shall it be, then, before you tell the people to return from following their brothers?"
\v 27 And Joab said, "As the \nd Lord\nd* lives, surely if you had not spoken then in the morning the people would have gone away and each would not have followed his brother."
\v 28 And Joab blew the trumpet and all the people stood still, and did not pursue Israel any more, nor did they fight any more.
\v 29 And Abiner and his men went all that night through the Arabah, and they passed over the Jordan, and went through all Bithron, and came to Mahanaim.
\v 30 And Joab returned from following Abiner, and when he had gathered all the people together, there were missing those of David's servants who had fallen: nineteen men and Asahel.
\v 31 And of the children of Benjamin and of Abiner's men the servants of David had struck 360 men.
\v 32 And they took up Asahel, and buried him in the sepulchre of his father, which was in Beth-lehem. And Joab and his men went all night, and the day broke on them at Hebron.
\c 3
\p
\v 1 And there was a long war between the house of Saul and the house of David, and David grew stronger and stronger, and the house of Saul grew weaker and weaker.
\v 2 And six sons were born to David in Hebron: his first-born was Aminon, by Ahinoam the Jezreelitess;
\v 3 and his second, Daluiah, by Abigail of Carmel; and the third, Abishalom the son of Maacah the daughter of Talmai king of Geshur;
\v 4 and the fourth, Adonijah the son of Haggith; and the fifth, Shephatiah by Abital;
\v 5 and the sixth, Ithream, by Eglah, David's wife. These were born to him, to David in Hebron.
\p
\v 6 And it happened, while there was war between the house of Saul and the house of David, that Abiner made himself strong in the house of Saul.
\v 7 And Saul had a concubine, whose name was Rizpah, the daughter of Aiah, and Abiner took her. And Eshbaal said to Abiner, "Why have you gone in to my father's concubine?"
\v 8 Then Abiner was very angry over this word of Eshbaal, and said, "Am I a dog's head? Is it for myself that I have done all these things today and shown kindness to the house of Saul your father, to his brothers, and to his friends, and have not made peace with the house of David? And yet this day you charge me with a fault concerning a woman.
\v 9 God do so to me, and more also, if I do not do to David as the \nd Lord\nd* has promised to him,
\v 10 to transfer the kingdom from the house of Saul, and to set up the throne of David over Israel and over Judah, from Dan even to Beer-sheba."
\v 11 And Eshbaal could not answer Abiner another word, because he feared him.
\p
\v 12 And Abiner sent messengers to David on his behalf, saying, "Make a covenant with me, and, behold, my hand shall be with you, to bring all Israel around to you."
\v 13 And David said, "Good! I will make a covenant with you, but I require one thing from you: you shall not see my face unless you bring Michal, Saul's daughter with you, when you come to see my face."
\v 14 And David sent messengers to Eshbaal, Saul's son, saying, "Give me my wife Michal, who I took for a hundred foreskins of the Philistines."
\v 15 And Eshbaal sent, and took her from her husband, Paltiel the son of Laish.
\v 16 And her husband went with her, weeping as he went, and followed her to Bahurim. Then Abiner said to him, "Go, return," and he returned.
\p
\v 17 And Abiner had a word with the elders of Israel, saying, "Previously you sought for David to be king over you.
\v 18 Now then do it, for the \nd Lord\nd* has spoken of David, saying, 'By the hand of my servant David I will save my people Israel out of the hand of the Philistines, and out of the hand of all their enemies.'"
\v 19 And Abiner also spoke in the ears of the children of Benjamin, and Abiner also went to Hebron to speak in the ears of David all that seemed good to Israel, and to the children of Benjamin.
\v 20 And Abiner came with twenty men to David at Hebron. And David made a feast for Abiner and the men who were with him.
\v 21 And Abiner said to David, "I will rise and go and gather all the people of Israel to my lord the king, that they may make a covenant with you, and that you may reign over all that your soul desires." And David sent Abiner away, and he went in peace.
\p
\v 22 And behold, the servants of David and Joab came from a foray, and brought in spoil with them. And Abiner was not with David in Hebron for he had sent him away, and he had gone in peace.
\v 23 When Joab and all the host who were with him had come, it was told to Joab, saying, "Abiner the son of Ner came to David, and he has sent him away, and he has gone in peace."
\v 24 Then Joab came to the king and said to him, "What have you done? Behold, Abiner the son of Ner came to you. Why have you sent him away, and he is quite gone?
\v 25 You know Abiner the son of Ner, that he came to deceive you and to know your going out and your coming in, and to know all that you are doing."
\p
\v 26 And when Joab had come out from David, he sent messengers after Abiner, and they brought him back from the well of Sirah, and David did not know about it.
\v 27 And when Abiner had returned to Hebron, Joab took him aside beside the gate to speak with him quietly, and struck him there in the body, and he died, for the blood of Asahel his brother.
\v 28 And afterward, when David heard it, he said, "My kingdom and I are guiltless before the \nd Lord\nd* from now on and forever, and may the blood of Abiner the son of Ner
\v 29 be on the head of Joab, and on all his father's house, and let there not fail from the house of Joab one who has an issue, or who is a leper, or who leans on a staff, or who falls by the sword, or who lacks bread."
\p
\v 30 And Joab and Abishai his brother killed Abiner, because he had lain in wait for their brother Asahel at Gibeon in the battle.
\v 31 And David said to Joab, and to all the people who were with him, "Tear your clothes, and clothe yourselves with sackcloth, and mourn before Abiner." And king David followed the bier.
\v 32 And they buried Abiner in Hebron. And the king lifted up his voice, and wept at the grave of Abiner, and all the people wept.
\v 33 And the king lamented for Abiner, and said,
\p
"Alas, Abiner has died as a fool dies.
\p
\v 34 Your hands were not bound, nor your feet put into fetters:
\p
As a fool falls, so did you fall."
\p
And all the people gathered to weep over him.
\v 35 And all the people came to make David eat bread while it was still day, and David promised, saying, "God do so to me, and more also, if I taste bread, or anything else, until the sun is down."
\v 36 And all the people took notice of it, and whatever the king did pleased all the people.
\v 37 And all the people and all Israel understood that day that the killing of Abiner the son of Ner was not from the king.
\v 38 And the king said to his servants, "Don't you know that a prince and a great man has fallen in Israel this day?
\v 39 And he was a relative and an appointed officer of the king this day, and these men the sons of Zeruiah are too hard for me. The \nd Lord\nd* reward the evil-doer according to his wickedness."
\c 4
\p
\v 1 And when Eshbaal, Saul's son, heard that Abiner was dead in Hebron, his hands became feeble, and all the Israelites were troubled.
\v 2 And Eshbaal, Saul's son, had two men who were captains of bands. The name of the one was Baanah, and the name of the other Rechab, the sons of Rimmon the Beerothite, of the children of Benjamin (for Beeroth is reckoned to Benjamin,
\v 3 and the Beerothites fled to Gittaim, and have been sojourners there until this day).
\p
\v 4 And Jonathan, Saul's son, had a son whose feet were lame. He was five years old when the news of Saul and Jonathan came out of Jezreel. And his nurse took him up, and fled. And it happened, as she hurried to flee, that he fell, and became lame. And his name was Mephibaal.
\p
\v 5 And the sons of Rimmon the Beerothite, Rechab and Baanah his brother, went, and came about the heat of the day to the house of Eshbaal, as he was resting at noon.
\v 6 And behold, the porter of the house had been gathering wheat, and she slumbered and fell asleep. And Rechab and Baanah his brother slipped past.
\v 7 And when they came into the house, as he lay on his bed in his bedroom, they struck him, and killed him, and cut off his head, and took it, and went by the way of the Arabah all night.
\v 8 And they brought the head of Eshbaal to David to Hebron, and said to the king, "Behold, the head of Eshbaal, the son of Saul, your enemy, who sought your life! The \nd Lord\nd* has avenged my lord the king this day on Saul, your enemy, and on his seed."
\v 9 And David answered Rechab and Baanah his brother, the sons of Rimmon the Beerothite, and said to them, "As the \nd Lord\nd* lives, who has redeemed my soul out of all adversity,
\v 10 when someone told me, saying, 'Behold, Saul is dead,' thinking to have brought good tidings, I took hold of him, and killed him in Ziklag. That was the reward I gave him for his tidings.
\v 11 How much more, when wicked men have killed a righteous person in his own house on his bed, shall I now seek his blood from your hand, and take you away from the earth."
\v 12 And David commanded his young men, and they killed them, and cut off their hands and their feet, and hung them up beside the pool in Hebron. And they buried the head of Eshbaal in the grave of Abiner in Hebron.
\c 5
\p
\v 1 Then all the rod-bearers of Israel came to David at Hebron, and spoke, saying, "Behold, we are your bone and your flesh.
\v 2 In the past, when Saul was king over us, you were the one who led Israel out and brought Israel in, and the \nd Lord\nd* said to you, 'You shall be shepherd of my people Israel, and you shall be prince over Israel.'"
\v 3 And all the elders of Israel came to the king at Hebron, and king David made a covenant with them in Hebron before the \nd Lord\nd*. And they anointed David king over all Israel.
\v 4 David was thirty years old when he became king, and he reigned forty years.
\v 5 He reigned over Judah in Hebron for seven years and six months, and he reigned over all Israel and Judah in Jerusalem for thirty three years.
\p
\v 6 And the king and his men went to Jerusalem against the Jebusites, the inhabitants of the land, who spoke to David, saying, "You shall not come in here," for the blind and the lame had incited them, saying, "David cannot come in here."
\v 7 And David took the stronghold of Zion. This is the city of David.
\v 8 And David said on that day, "Whoever strikes the Jebusites, let him get up to the watercourse, and \add strike\add* the lame and the blind, who are hated of David's soul." Therefore they say, "There are the blind and the lame, he cannot come into the house."
\p
\v 9 And David lived in the stronghold, and called it the city of David. And he built the city round about from Millo and inward.
\v 10 And David grew greater and greater, for the \nd Lord\nd*, the God of hosts, was with him.
\v 11 And Hiram king of Tyre sent messengers to David, and cedar-trees, and carpenters, and builders of walls, and they built David a house.
\v 12 And David perceived that the \nd Lord\nd* had established him as king over Israel, and that his kingdom was exalted for the sake of his people Israel.
\v 13 And David took for himself more concubines and wives out of Jerusalem, after he had come from Hebron, and more sons and daughters were born to David.
\v 14 And these are the names of those who were born to him in Jerusalem: Shammua, and Shobab, and Nathan, and Solomon,
\v 15 and Ibhar, and Elishua, and Eliphelet, and Nogah, and Nepheg, and Japhia,
\v 16 and Elishama, and Beeliada, and Eliphelet.
\p
\v 17 And when the Philistines heard that David had been anointed king over Israel, the Philistines went up to look for David. And David heard of it, and went down to the stronghold.
\v 18 And the Philistines had come and made a raid in the valley of Rephaim.
\v 19 And David inquired of the \nd Lord\nd*, saying, "Shall I go up against the Philistines? Will you give them into my hand?" And the \nd Lord\nd* said to David, "Go up, for I will certainly give them into your hand."
\v 20 And David came to Baal-perazim\f + \fr 5:20 \ft That is, Master of the breaches.\f*, and David struck them there, and David said, "The \nd Lord\nd* has broken my enemies before me, like the breach of waters." Therefore he called the name of that place Baal-perazim.
\v 21 And the Philistines left their gods there, and David and his men took them away, and David spoke, and they were burned with fire.
\p
\v 22 And the Philistines came up yet again, and made a raid in the valley of Rephaim.
\v 23 And when David inquired of the \nd Lord\nd*, he said, "You shall not go up. Circle behind them, and come on them over against Bacaim.
\v 24 And it shall be, when you hear the sound of turmoil in the groves\f + \fr 5:24 \ft Or, Asherim.\f* of Bacaim, then you shall stir yourself, for then the \nd Lord\nd* has gone out before you to strike the host of the Philistines."
\v 25 And David did so, as the \nd Lord\nd* commanded him, and struck the Philistines from Gibeon until Gezer.
\c 6
\p
\v 1 And David again gathered together all the chosen men of Israel, 70,000 \add men\add*.
\v 2 And David rose, and went with all the people who were with him, from Baalah, that is Kiriath-jearim, which belongs to Judah, to bring up from there the ark of God which is called by the name of the \nd Lord\nd* of hosts who sits \add above\add* the cherubim.
\v 3 And they set the ark of God on a new cart, and brought it out of the house of Abinadab that was in the hill. And Uzzah and Ahio, the sons of Abinadab, were leading the new cart
\v 4 with the ark, and Uzzah was walking alongside and Ahio was walking ahead of the ark.
\v 5 And David and all the children of Israel played before the \nd Lord\nd* with all their might, with songs, and with harps, and with psalteries, and with timbrels, and with castanets, and with cymbals.
\p
\v 6 And when they came to the threshing-floor of Chidon, Uzzah put his hand out onto the ark to take hold of it, for the oxen stumbled.
\v 7 And the anger of the \nd Lord\nd* was kindled against Uzzah, and God struck him there because he put his hand out onto the ark. And he died there by the ark of God.
\v 8 And David was displeased, because the \nd Lord\nd* had broken forth on Uzzah, and he called that place Perez-uzzah\f + \fr 6:8 \ft That is, Breach of Uzzah.\f*, to this day.
\p
\v 9 And David was afraid of the \nd Lord\nd* that day, and he said, "How shall the ark of the \nd Lord\nd* come to me?" And when the ark of the \nd Lord\nd* came,
\v 10 David was unwilling to remove the ark of the \nd Lord\nd* to himself in the city of David, and David carried it aside into the house of Obed-edom the Gittite.
\v 11 And the ark of the \nd Lord\nd* remained in the house of Obed-edom the Gittite three months. And the \nd Lord\nd* blessed Obed-edom, and all his house.
\p
\v 12 And it was told king David, saying, "The \nd Lord\nd* has blessed the house of Obed-edom and all that is his because of the ark of God." And David said, "I will bring the blessing back to my house." And David went and brought up the ark of the \nd Lord\nd* from the house of Obed-edom into the city of David with joy.
\v 13 And seven companies were with him bearing the ark, and he sacrificed an ox and a fatling.
\v 14 And David danced before the \nd Lord\nd* with all his might. And he was girded with a linen ephod.
\v 15 And David and all the house of Israel brought up the ark of the \nd Lord\nd* with shouting, and with the sound of the trumpet.
\p
\v 16 And it happened, as the ark of the \nd Lord\nd* came into the city of David, that Michal the daughter of Saul looked down through the window, and saw king David leaping and dancing before the \nd Lord\nd*, and she despised him in her heart.
\v 17 And they brought in the ark of the \nd Lord\nd*, and set it inside the tent that David had pitched for it. And David offered burnt-offerings and peace-offerings before the \nd Lord\nd*.
\v 18 And when David had finished offering the burnt-offerings and the peace-offerings, he blessed the people in the name of the \nd Lord\nd* of hosts.
\v 19 And he distributed among all the people, from Dan to Beersheba, among the whole multitude of Israel, both to men and women, to every one a cake of bread, and a portion, and a cake of raisins. And all the people left, every one to his house.
\p
\v 20 Then David returned to bless his household. And Michal the daughter of Saul came out to meet David, and greeted him and said, "How glorious was the king of Israel today, who uncovered himself today in the eyes of the handmaids of his servants, as one of the dancers shamelessly uncovers himself!"
\v 21 And David said to Michal, "Before the \nd Lord\nd* I will dance. Blessed be the \nd Lord\nd* who chose me above your father, and above all his house, to appoint me prince over his people, over Israel; therefore I will play and dance before the \nd Lord\nd*.
\v 22 And I will uncover myself like this again and I will be lowly in your eyes, and with the handmaids you spoke about, with them I will be honoured."
\v 23 And Michal the daughter of Saul had no child to the day of her death.
\c 7
\p
\v 1 And it happened, when the king lived in his house, and the \nd Lord\nd* had given him rest from all his enemies all around,
\v 2 that the king said to Nathan the prophet, "See now, I live in a house of cedar, and the ark of God lives inside curtains of the \nd Lord\nd*.
\v 3 And Nathan said to the king, "Go, do all that is in your heart, for God is with you."
\p
\v 4 And it happened on the same night, that the word of the \nd Lord\nd* came to Nathan the prophet, saying,
\v 5 "Go and tell my servant David, 'Thus says the \nd Lord\nd*,
\p
"You are not the one who should build a house for me to live in,
\v 6 for I have not lived in a house since the day I brought the children of Israel up out of Egypt, even to this day, and have walked in a tent, in a tabernacle.
\v 7 In all places where I have walked with all Israel, did I speak a word with one of the rod-bearers of Israel, who I commanded to be shepherd of my people Israel, saying, "Why haven't you\sup ‡\sup* built me a house of cedar?"'
\p
\v 8 "And now you shall say thus to my servant David, 'Thus says the \nd Lord\nd* of hosts,
\p
"I took you from the habitation, from following the sheep, to be prince over my people, over Israel,
\v 9 and I have been with you wherever you went, and have cut off all your enemies from before you, and I will make you a great name, like the name of the great ones who are in the earth.
\v 10 And I will appoint a place for my people Israel, and will plant them, that they may live in their own place, and not tremble any more. Neither shall the son of wickedness afflict them any more, as at the first,
\v 11 and from the day that I commanded judges to be over my people Israel. And I will cause you to rest from all your enemies. Moreover the \nd Lord\nd* tells you that, as for a house, the \nd Lord\nd* will make one for you.
\p
\v 12 "When your days are fulfilled, and you sleep with your fathers, I will set up your seed after you, who shall come from your body\f + \fr 7:12 \ft Hebrew: inward parts. The word is used to refer to either reproductive (as here) or digestive organs.\f*, and I will establish his kingdom.
\v 13 He shall build me a house for my name, and I will establish his throne forever.
\v 14 I will be his father, and he shall be my son. When he sins I will chasten him with the rod of men, and with the strokes of the children of men.
\v 15 And I will not take my lovingkindness away from him, as I took it from the one I put away before you.
\v 16 And his house and his kingdom shall be made sure forever before my face. And his throne shall be established forever."'"
\p
\v 17 According to all these words, and according to all this vision, so Nathan spoke to David.
\p
\v 18 Then David the king went in, and sat before the \nd Lord\nd*, and he said,
\p
"Who am I, O \nd Lord\nd* the \nd Lord\nd*, and what is my house, that you have brought me this far?
\v 19 And this was a small thing in your eyes, O \nd Lord\nd* the \nd Lord\nd*, and you have spoken of your servant's house concerning a time far off, and this is the law of men, O \nd Lord\nd* the \nd Lord\nd*!
\v 20 And what more can David say to you? For you know your servant, O \nd Lord\nd* the \nd Lord\nd*.
\v 21 For your servant's sake, and according to your own heart, you have done all this greatness, to make your servant know it.
\v 22 Therefore you are great, O \nd Lord\nd* the \nd Lord\nd*, for there is none like you, neither is there any God besides you, according to all that we have heard with our ears.
\p
\v 23 "And what other nation on earth is like your people, like Israel, who God went to redeem for you as a people, to make you a name, and to do for you a great and awesome thing in driving out, before your people who you have redeemed for yourself from Egypt, a nation and its tents?
\v 24 And you established for yourself your people Israel to be your people forever, and you, the \nd Lord\nd*, became their God.
\p
\v 25 "And now, O \nd Lord\nd* the \nd Lord\nd*, let the word that you have spoken concerning your servant, and concerning his house, be established forever, and do as you have spoken.
\v 26 And let your name be magnified forever, saying, 'The \nd Lord\nd* of hosts is God over Israel,' and the house of your servant David shall be established before you.
\v 27 For you, O \nd Lord\nd* of hosts, the God of Israel, have revealed to your servant, saying, 'I will build you a house.' Therefore your servant has found in his heart in God to pray this prayer to you.
\p
\v 28 "And now, O \nd Lord\nd* the \nd Lord\nd*, you are God, and your words are truth, and you have promised this good thing concerning your servant.
\v 29 And now let it please you to bless the house of your servant, that it may continue forever before you. For you, O \nd Lord\nd* the \nd Lord\nd*, have spoken it, and with your blessing let the house of your servant be blessed forever."
\c 8
\p
\v 1 And after this it happened that David struck the Philistines, and subdued them, and David took the suburbs out of the hand of the Philistines.
\p
\v 2 And he struck Moab, and measured them with the line, making them to lie down on the ground. And two lines were to be put to death, and one full line to be kept alive. And the Moabites became servants to David, and brought tribute.
\p
\v 3 David also struck Hadarezer the son of Rehob, king of Zobah, as he went to recover his dominion at the River Euphrates.
\v 4 And David took from him 1,000 chariots and 7,000 horsemen, and 20,000 footmen, and David hocked all the chariot horses, and reserved \add enough\add* of them for a hundred chariots for himself.
\p
\v 5 And when the Arameans of Damascus came to help Hadarezer king of Zobah, David struck 22,000 men of the Arameans.
\v 6 Then David put an officer in Aram of Damascus, and the Arameans became servants to David, and brought tribute. And the \nd Lord\nd* gave victory to David wherever he went.
\p
\v 7 And David took the shields of gold that were on the servants of Hadarezer king of Zobah, and brought them to Jerusalem. (And Shishak king of Egypt took them when he came up to Jerusalem in the days of Rehoboam son of Solomon.)
\v 8 And from Tebah and from the choice cities of Hadarezer, king David took very much bronze, and with it Solomon made the bronze sea and the pillars and the basin and all the bronze utensils.
\p
\v 9 And when Tou, king of Hamath heard that David had struck all the host of Hadarezer,
\v 10 then Tou sent Hadoram his son to king David, to salute him, and to bless him, because he had fought against Hadarezer and had struck him, for Hadarezer had wars with Tou. And he brought with him vessels of silver, and vessels of gold, and vessels of bronze.
\v 11 King David also dedicated these to the \nd Lord\nd*, with the silver and gold that he dedicated from all the nations which he subdued;
\v 12 of Edom, and of Moab, and of the children of Ammon, and of the Philistines, and of Amalek, and of the spoil of Hadarezer, son of Rehob, king of Zobah.
\p
\v 13 And David got himself a name, and when he returned he killed 18,000 Edomites in the Valley of Salt.
\v 14 And David put garrisons in Edom. He put garrisons throughout all Edom and all in Edom were servants to David. And the \nd Lord\nd* saved David wherever he went.
\p
\v 15 And David reigned over all Israel, and David executed justice and righteousness to all his people.
\v 16 And Joab the son of Zeruiah was over the host, and Jehoshaphat the son of Ahilud was recorder,
\v 17 and Zadok the son of Ahitub and Ahimelech the son of Abiathar were priests, and Shavsha was scribe,
\v 18 and Benaiah the son of Jehoiada was over the Cherethites and the Pelethites, and David's sons were princes.
\c 9
\p
\v 1 And David said, "Is there still anyone left from the house of Saul, that I may show him kindness for Jonathan's sake?"
\v 2 And there was a servant of the house of Saul whose name was Ziba, and they called him to David, and the king said to him, "Are you Ziba the servant?" And he said, "Your servant is he."
\v 3 And the king said, "Isn't there anyone left from the house of Saul, who I may show the kindness of God?" And Ziba said to the king, "Jonathan still has a son, who has lame feet."
\v 4 And the king said to him, "Where is he?" And Ziba said to the king, "Behold, he is in the house of Machir the son of Ammiel, in Lo-debar."
\p
\v 5 Then king David sent, and fetched him out of the house of Machir the son of Ammiel, from Lo-debar.
\v 6 And Mephibaal, the son of Jonathan, the son of Saul, came to David, and fell on his face, and did obeisance to him. And David said to him, "Mephibaal." And he answered, "Behold, your servant!"
\v 7 And David said to him, "Don't be afraid, for I will surely show you kindness for the sake of Jonathan your father, and will restore you all the land of Saul your father, and you will eat bread at my table continually."
\v 8 And he did obeisance, and said, "What is your servant, that you should look on such a dead dog as I am?"
\p
\v 9 Then the king called to Ziba, Saul's servant, and said to him, "All that belonged to Saul and to all his house I have given to your master's son.
\v 10 And you shall till the land for him, you, and your sons, and your servants, and you shall bring food into your master's house and they will eat, and Mephibaal your master's son shall always eat bread at my table." And Ziba had fifteen sons and twenty servants.
\v 11 Then Ziba said to the king, "According to all that my lord the king commands his servant, so shall your servant do." And Mephibaal ate at the king's table, as one of the king's sons.
\p
\v 12 And Mephibaal had a young son, whose name was Mica. And all who lived in the house of Ziba were servants to Mephibaal.
\v 13 And Mephibaal lived in Jerusalem, for he ate continually at the king's table. And he was lame in both his feet.
\c 10
\p
\v 1 And it happened after this, that the king of the children of Ammon died, and Hanun his son reigned in his place.
\v 2 And David said, "I will show kindness to Hanun the son of Nahash, as his father showed kindness to me." And David sent to comfort him concerning his father by the hand of his servants. And David's servants came into the land of the children of Ammon.
\v 3 And the princes of the children of Ammon said to Hanun their lord, "Is David honouring your father in your eyes because he has sent comforters to you? Hasn't David sent his servants to you to search the city, and to spy it out, and to overthrow it?"
\v 4 And Hanun took David's servants, and shaved off their beards, and cut off their garments in the middle, even to their buttocks, and sent them away.
\v 5 And when David was told about the men, he sent to meet them, for the men were greatly ashamed. And the king said, "Stay in Jericho until your beards have grown, and then return."
\p
\v 6 And when the children of Ammon saw that they stank to David, the children of Ammon sent and hired the Arameans of Beth-rehob, and the Arameans of Zobah, 20,000 footmen, and the king of Maacah with 1,000 men, and the men of Tob: 12,000 men.
\v 7 And when David heard of it, he sent Joab, and all the host of the mighty men.
\v 8 And the children of Ammon came out, and put the battle in array at the entrance of the city. And the Arameans of Zobah and of Rehob, and the men of Tob and Maacah, were by themselves in the field.
\v 9 And when Joab saw that the battle was set against him before and behind, he chose from all the choice men of Israel, and put them in array against the Arameans.
\v 10 And the rest of the people he gave into the hand of Abishai his brother, and he put them in array against the children of Ammon.
\v 11 And Joab said to Abishai, "If the Arameans are too strong for me then you shall help me, and if the children of Ammon are too strong for you then I will come and help you.
\v 12 Be strong, and let us be strong and fight for our people, and for the cities of our God, and the \nd Lord\nd* do that which is good in his eyes concerning us."
\p
\v 13 And Joab and the people who were with him approached the battle against the Arameans, and the Arameans fled before him.
\v 14 And when the children of Ammon saw that the Arameans had fled, they likewise fled before Abishai, and entered into the city. Then Joab returned from the children of Ammon, and came to Jerusalem.
\v 15 And when Aram saw that they were beaten before the children of Israel, they gathered themselves together.
\v 16 And Hadarezer sent, and brought out the Arameans who were beyond the River, and they came to Helam, with Shobach the captain of the host of Hadarezer at their head.
\v 17 And it was told David, and he gathered all Israel together, and passed over the Jordan, and came to Helam. And the Arameans set themselves in array against David, and fought with him.
\v 18 And the Arameans fled before Israel, and David killed 7,000 charioteers, and 40,000 foot soldiers of Aram, and struck Shobach the captain of their host and he died there.
\v 19 And when all the kings who were servants to Hadarezer saw that they were beaten before Israel, they made peace with Israel, and served them. And the Arameans feared to help the children of Ammon any more.
\c 11
\p
\v 1 And it happened, at the return of the year, at the time when kings go out, that David sent Joab together with his servants and all Israel and they destroyed the children of Ammon, and besieged Rabbah. And David stayed in Jerusalem.
\v 2 And it happened at evening, that David rose from his bed, and walked on the roof of the king's house. And from the roof he saw a woman bathing, and the woman was very beautiful in appearance.
\v 3 And David sent and asked about the woman. And \add someone\add* said, "Isn't this Bath-sheba, the daughter of Eliam, the wife of Uriah the Hittite?"
\v 4 And David sent messengers, and took her, and he went in to her, and he lay with her, and she purified herself from her uncleanness, and she returned to her house.
\p
\v 5 And the woman conceived, and she sent and told David, and said, "I am with child."
\v 6 And David sent to Joab and said, "Send me Uriah the Hittite." And Joab sent Uriah to him.
\v 7 And when Uriah had come to David, David asked him about Joab's peace and the peace of the people and the peace of the war. And he said, "There is peace."
\v 8 And David said to Uriah, "Go down to your house, and wash your feet." And Uriah left the king's presence, and he went out after those who stand by the king.
\v 9 And Uriah slept at the door of the king's house with all the servants of his lord, and did not go down to his house.
\p
\v 10 And when they had told David the king, saying, "Uriah did not go down to his house," David said to Uriah, "Haven't you come from a journey? And why didn't you go down to your house?"
\v 11 And Uriah said to David, "If the holy ark, and Israel, and Judah, live in booths, and my lord Joab, and the servants of my lord, are camped in the open field, how then shall I go into my house, to eat and to drink, and to lie with my wife? As your soul lives, I will not do this thing."
\v 12 And David said to Uriah, "Stay here today too, and tomorrow I will let you leave." And Uriah stayed in Jerusalem that day. And on the following day
\v 13 David called him and he ate and drank before him, and he became drunk. And at evening Uriah went out and lay on a bed with the servants of his lord, and he did not go down to his house.
\v 14 And it happened in the morning, that David wrote a letter to Joab, and sent it by the hand of Uriah.
\v 15 And he wrote in the letter, saying, "Put Uriah into the strong fighting and withdraw from him, so that he may be struck and die."
\v 16 And it happened, when Joab kept watch on the city, that he assigned Uriah to a weak place because he knew there were valiant men.
\v 17 And the men of the city went out, and fought with Joab, and some of the people fell there according to David's words, and Uriah the Hittite died too.
\p
\v 18 Then Joab sent and told David all the things concerning the war,
\v 19 and Joab charged the messenger, saying, "When you have finished telling the king all the things concerning the war,
\v 20 it shall be that, if the king's anger rises, and he says to you, 'Why did you\sup ‡\sup* go so near the city to fight? Didn't you\sup ‡\sup* know they would shoot from the wall?
\v 21 Who struck Abimelech the son of Jerubbaal? Didn't a woman throw an upper millstone on him from the wall, and he died at Thebez? Why did you\sup ‡\sup* go so near the wall?' then you shall say, 'The men prevailed against us and came out against us in the field, and we were upon them as far as the entrance of the city. And it was heavy with arrows on your servants from the wall, so some eighteen of the king's servants are dead, and your servant Uriah the Hittite is dead also.'"
\p
\v 22 And the messenger went, and came to the king in Jerusalem and showed David all that Joab had sent him for. And David's anger burned against Joab, and he said to the messenger, "Why did you\sup ‡\sup* go so near the city to fight? Didn't you\sup ‡\sup* know they would shoot from the wall? Who struck down Abimelech the son of Jerubbaal? Didn't a woman throw an upper millstone on him from the wall, and he died at Thebez? Why did you\sup ‡\sup* go so near the wall?"
\v 23 And the messenger said to David, "The men prevailed against us, and came out to us into the field, and we were upon them as far as the entrance of the city.
\v 24 And it was heavy with arrows on your servants from the wall, so some eighteen of the king's servants are dead, and your servant Uriah the Hittite is dead also."
\v 25 Then David said to the messenger, "Thus shall you say to Joab, 'Don't let this thing be evil in your eyes, for the sword consumes one as well as another. Make your battle stronger against the city, and overthrow it.'"
\p
\v 26 And when the wife of Uriah heard that Uriah her husband was dead, she mourned for her husband.
\v 27 And when the mourning was past, David sent and took Bathsheba to his house, and she became his wife, and bore him a son.
\p
And the thing that David had done displeased the \nd Lord\nd*.
\c 12
\p
\v 1 And the \nd Lord\nd* sent Nathan the prophet to David. And Nathan came to David, and said to him, "Judge this case for me. There were two men in one city, one rich, and the other poor.
\v 2 The rich man had very many flocks and herds,
\v 3 and the poor man had nothing, except one little ewe lamb, which he had bought and kept safe and nourished. And it grew up together with him, and with his children, it ate from his own morsel, and drank from his own cup, and lay on his chest, and was like a daughter to him.
\v 4 And a stranger came to the rich man, and he spared his own flock and his own herd from being taken to prepare for the wayfarer who had come to him, and took the poor man's lamb, and slaughtered it for the man who had come to him."
\p
\v 5 And David's anger was greatly kindled against the man, and he said to Nathan, "As the \nd Lord\nd* lives, the man who has done this is a son of death,
\v 6 and he shall restore the lamb fourfold, because he did this thing, and because he had no pity."
\v 7 And Nathan said to David, "You are the man. For thus says the \nd Lord\nd*, the God of Israel, 'I anointed you king over Israel, and I delivered you out of the hand of Saul,
\v 8 and I gave you your master's house, and your master's wives into your bosom, and gave you the house of Israel and of Judah, and if that had been too little, I would have added to you as many again as these.
\v 9 Why have you despised the \nd Lord\nd*, to do that which is evil in his sight? You have struck Uriah the Hittite with the sword, and have taken his wife to be your wife, and have killed him with the sword of the children of Ammon.
\v 10 And now the sword shall never leave your house, because you have despised me, and have taken the wife of Uriah the Hittite to be your wife.'
\v 11 Thus says the \nd Lord\nd*, 'Behold, I will raise up evil against you out of your own house, and I will take your wives before your eyes, and give them to your neighbour, and he shall lie with your wives in the sight of this sun.
\v 12 For you did it secretly, and I will do this thing before all Israel, and before this sun.'"
\p
\v 13 And David said to Nathan, "I have sinned against the \nd Lord\nd*." And Nathan said to David, "The \nd Lord\nd* has also put your sin away, you shall not die.
\v 14 However, because by this deed you have despised the \nd Lord\nd* the child also who is born to you shall surely die."
\p
\v 15 And Nathan departed to his house. And God struck the child that Uriah's wife bore to David, and it was very sick.
\v 16 And David sought God for the child, and David fasted, and went in, and lay all night in sackcloth on the earth.
\v 17 And the elders of his house came near him, to raise him up from the earth, and he would not, neither did he eat bread with them.
\v 18 And it happened on the seventh day, that the child died. And the servants of David feared to tell him that the child was dead, for they said, "Behold, while the child was still alive, we spoke to him to raise him up from the ground, and he did not listen to our voice. How will he then vex himself, if we tell him that the child is dead!"
\v 19 And when David saw that his servants were whispering together, David perceived that the child was dead, and David said to his servants, "Is the child dead?" And they said, "He is dead."
\p
\v 20 Then David rose from the earth, and washed, and anointed himself, and changed his clothes. And he came into the house of the \nd Lord\nd*, and worshipped, then he came to his own house and he asked for food to eat, and food was brought before him, and he ate.
\v 21 Then his servants said to him, "What is this thing you have done? While the child was alive, you fasted and wept and watched; and when the child was dead, you rose and ate food and drank."
\v 22 And he said, "While the child was still alive I fasted and wept, for I said, 'Who knows whether the \nd Lord\nd* will not be gracious to me, that the child may live?'
\v 23 And now the child is dead, why should I fast? Can I bring him back? I shall go to him, and he will not return to me."
\p
\v 24 And David comforted Bath-sheba his wife, and went in to her, and she lay with him, and she bore a son, and he called his name Solomon. And the \nd Lord\nd* loved him
\v 25 and he sent by the hand of Nathan the prophet, and he called his name Jedidiah\f + \fr 12:25 \ft That is, beloved of the Lord.\f*, by the word of the \nd Lord\nd*.
\p
\v 26 And Joab fought against Rabbah of the children of Ammon, and took the royal city.
\v 27 And Joab sent messengers to David, and said, "I have fought against Rabbah, also I have taken the city of waters.
\v 28 And now gather the rest of the people together, and camp against the city, and take it yourself, lest I take the city, and it be called after my name."
\v 29 And David gathered all the people together, and went to Rabbah, and fought against it, and took it.
\v 30 And he took the crown of their king from his head, and the weight of it was a talent of gold and there was a precious stone, and it was set on David's head. And he brought out the spoil of the city in great abundance.
\v 31 And he brought forth the people who were in it, and cut it with saws, and with harrows of iron, and with axes of iron; and he made them pass to the brickwork. And thus he did to all the cities of the children of Ammon. And David and all the people returned to Jerusalem.
\c 13
\p
\v 1 And it happened after this, that Abishalom the son of David had a sister very beautiful in appearance, whose name was Tamar, and Aminon the son of David loved her.
\v 2 And Aminon was so distressed that he became sick because of his sister Tamar, for she was a virgin and it seemed hard to Aminon to do anything to her.
\v 3 And Aminon had a friend, whose name was Jonathan, the son of Shimeah, David's brother, and Jonathan was very subtle.
\v 4 And he said to Aminon, "O son of the king, why are you so poor from day to day? Won't you tell me?" And Aminon said to him, "I love Tamar, my brother Abishalom's sister."
\v 5 And Jonathan said to him, "Lie down on your bed, and pretend to be sick, and when your father comes to visit you, say to him, 'Please let my sister Tamar come and give me to eat, and prepare the food in my sight, that I may see it and eat it from her hand.'"
\p
\v 6 And Aminon lay down, and pretended to be sick, and when the king had come to visit him, Aminon said to the king, "Let my sister Tamar come to me, please, and make me a couple of cakes in my sight, that I may eat from her hand."
\v 7 Then David sent home to Tamar, saying, "Go to your brother Aminon now, and prepare food for him.
\v 8 And Tamar went to her brother Aminon, and he was lying down. And Tamar took dough, and kneaded it, and made cakes in his sight, and baked the cakes.
\v 9 And she took the pan and poured them out before him and he refused to eat. And Aminon said, "Make all the men go out from me." And they made all the men go out from him.
\p
\v 10 And Aminon said to Tamar, "Bring the food into the chamber, that I may eat from your hand." And Tamar took the cakes which she had made, and brought them into the chamber to Aminon her brother.
\v 11 And when she had brought them near him to eat, he took hold of her, and said to her, "Come, lie with me."
\v 12 And she answered him, "No, my brother, do not force me, for no such thing ought to be done in Israel. Don't do this folly.
\v 13 And where wouldn't my reproach go? And as for you, you will be as one of the fools in Israel. And now, please speak to the king, for he will not withhold me from you."
\v 14 And he would not listen to her, and being stronger than she, he forced her, and lay with her.
\p
\v 15 Then Aminon hated her with very great hatred, for the hatred with which he hated her was greater than the love with which he had loved her. And Aminon said to her, "Arise, be gone."
\v 16 And she said to him, "No, my brother, because this latter evil in putting me out is greater than the former that you did to me." And he would not listen to her.
\v 17 Then he called his servant who ministered to him, and said to him, "Put this woman out from me now, and bolt the door after her."
\p
\v 18 And she had a varicoloured\f + \fr 13:18 \ft Like Joseph's in Genesis 37:3.\f* garment on her, for like that the king's daughters who were virgins clothed themselves in their robes. Then his servant brought her out, and bolted the door after her.
\v 19 And Tamar took ashes and put them on her head, and tore her varicoloured garment that was on her, and she laid her hands on her head, and went her way, crying aloud as she went.
\v 20 And Abishalom her brother said to her, "Has Aminon your brother been with you? And now hold your peace, my sister. He is your brother, do not set your heart to say anything." And Tamar remained and was desolate in her brother Abishalom's house.
\p
\v 21 And when king David heard of all these things, he was very angry, but did nothing to pain his son Aminon, for he loved him because he was his firstborn.
\v 22 And Abishalom spoke neither good nor bad to Aminon, for Abishalom hated Aminon, because he had forced his sister Tamar.
\p
\v 23 And it happened after two years, that Abishalom had sheep-shearers in Baal-hazor, which is beside Ephron, and Abishalom invited all the king's sons.
\v 24 And Abishalom came to the king, and said, "Behold now, your servant has sheep-shearers. Please let the king and his servants go to his servant."
\v 25 And the king said to Abishalom, "No, my son, let us not all go, lest we be burdensome to you." And he urged him, and the king would not go, and blessed him.
\v 26 Then Abishalom said, "If not, please let my brother Aminon go with me." And the king said, "Why should he go with you?"
\v 27 And Abishalom urged him, and he let Aminon and all the king's sons go with him.
\p
And Abishalom made a banquet like a king's banquet.
\v 28 And Abishalom commanded his servants, saying, "Now see, when Aminon's heart is merry with wine, and when I say to you, "Strike Aminon," then kill him. Do not fear, for I have commanded you. Be courageous, and be valiant men."
\v 29 And the servants of Abishalom did to Aminon as Abishalom had commanded. Then all the king's sons arose, and every man got onto his mule, and fled.
\p
\v 30 And it happened, while they were on the way, that the news came to David, saying, "Abishalom has killed all the king's sons, and there is not one of them left."
\v 31 Then the king rose, and tore his garments, and lay on the earth, and all his servants stood by with their clothes torn.
\v 32 And Jonadab, the son of Shimeah, David's brother, answered and said, "Don't let my lord the king say that all the young men the king's sons are dead, for Aminon only is dead: because Abishalom has been angry against him from the day that he forced his sister Tamar.
\v 33 And now don't let my lord the king take the thing to his heart, saying that all the king's sons are dead, for Aminon only is dead."
\p
\v 34 And Abishalom fled. And the young man that kept the watch lifted up his eyes, and looked, and, behold, many people came by the Horonaim road by the side of the mountain in the descent. And the watchman came and told the king, and said, "I have seen men on the Horonaim road by the side of the mountain."
\v 35 And Jonadab said to the king, "Behold, the king's sons have come. As your servant said, so it is."
\v 36 And it happened, as soon as he had finished speaking, that behold, the king's sons came, and lifted up their voice, and wept. And the king also and all his servants wept with a very great weeping.
\p
\v 37 And Abishalom fled, and went to Talmai the son of Ammihur, king of Geshur. And the king mourned for his son every day.
\v 38 And Abishalom fled, and went to Geshur in the region of Helam, and was there three years.
\v 39 And the spirit of the king stopped going out against Abishalom, for he was comforted concerning Aminon, seeing he was dead.
\c 14
\p
\v 1 And Joab the son of Zeruiah knew that the king's heart was on Abishalom.
\v 2 And Joab sent to Tekoa, and fetched from there a wise woman, and said to her, "Please pretend to be a mourner, and put on mourning clothes, and please, do not anoint yourself with oil, and be as a woman who has mourned a long time for the dead,
\v 3 and go in to the king, and speak in this manner to him." And Joab put the words in her mouth.
\p
\v 4 And when the woman of Tekoa came to the king, she fell on her face to the ground, and did obeisance, and said, "Help, O king, help."
\v 5 And the king said to her, "What ails you?" And the woman answered, "Truly, I am a widow, and my husband is dead.
\v 6 And your handmaid had two sons, and they struggled together in the field, and there was no mediator between them, and one struck his brother, and killed him.
\v 7 And, behold, the whole family has risen against your handmaid, saying, "Deliver him who struck his brother, that we may kill him for the life of his brother who he killed," and destroy your heir. Thus they will quench the one coal that I have left to me, and will leave to my husband neither name nor remainder on the face of the earth."
\p
\v 8 And the king said to the woman, "Go to your house in peace, and I will give charge concerning you."
\v 9 And the woman of Tekoa said to the king, "My lord, O king, the iniquity be on me and on my father's house, and the king and the king's throne be guiltless."
\v 10 And the king said, "Whoever says a word to you, bring him to me, and he shall not touch you any more."
\v 11 Then said she, "Please, let my lord the king remember the \nd Lord\nd* your God, that the avengers of blood not destroy any more, lest you destroy my son." And the king said, "As the \nd Lord\nd* lives, not one hair of your son shall fall to the earth."
\p
\v 12 Then the woman of Tekoa said, "Let your handmaid, please, speak a word to my lord the king." And the king said, "Say on."
\v 13 And the woman said, "Why then have you devised such a thing against the people of the \nd Lord\nd*? For because the king has put aside this thing, the king is as one who is guilty, in that the king does not fetch home again the one banished from him.
\v 14 For your son is dead, and as water spilled on the ground cannot be gathered up again, he cannot take up his soul again, yet the king thinks to banish the banished one from him.
\v 15 And now, seeing that I have come to speak this word to the king, it is because the people have made me afraid, and your handmaid said, 'Your handmaid will now speak to the king. It may be that the king will perform the request of his servant.
\v 16 For the king will hear, and deliver his servant out of the hand of the man who is seeking to destroy me and my son together out of the inheritance of the \nd Lord\nd*.'
\v 17 Then your handmaid said, 'Please let the word of my lord the king be comfortable, for as an angel of the \nd Lord\nd*, so is my lord the king to discern good and bad, and the \nd Lord\nd* your God will be with you.'"
\p
\v 18 Then the king answered and said to the woman, "Please do not hide from me anything that I shall ask you." And the woman said, "Let my lord the king now speak."
\v 19 And the king said, "Is the hand of Joab with you in all this?" And the woman answered and said to the king, "As your soul lives, my lord the king, none can turn to the right hand or to the left from anything that my lord the king has spoken, for your servant Joab, he told me, and he put all these words in the mouth of your handmaid.
\v 20 Your servant Joab has done this thing to change the face of the matter. And my lord is wise, according to the wisdom of an angel of God, to know what is in the earth."
\p
\v 21 And the king said to Joab, "Behold now, I will do according to your advice. And go, bring the young man Abishalom back."
\v 22 And Joab fell to the ground on his face, and did obeisance, and blessed the king. And Joab said, "Today your servant knows that I have found favor in your sight, my lord, O king, in that the king has performed the request of his servant."
\v 23 And Joab rose and went to Geshur, and brought Abishalom to Jerusalem.
\v 24 And the king said, Let him turn to his own house, and let him not see my face. And Abishalom turned to his own house, and did not see the king's face.
\p
\v 25 And there was no one in Israel to be praised for his beauty as much as Abishalom. From the sole of his foot even to the crown of his head there was no blemish in him.
\v 26 And when he cut the hair of his head (now it was at every year's end that he cut it, because it was heavy on him, and he cut it), he weighed the hair of his head at 100 shekels, by the king's shekel.
\v 27 And to Abishalom there were born three sons, and one daughter, whose name was Maacah. She was a woman of a beautiful appearance, and she became the wife of Rehoboam son of Solomon, and bore to him Abijah.
\p
\v 28 And Abishalom lived two full years in Jerusalem and he did not see the king's face.
\v 29 Then Abishalom sent for Joab, to send him to the king, and Joab would not come to him. And he sent again a second time, and he would not come.
\v 30 And Abishalom said to his servants, "See, Joab's portion in the field is near ours, and he has barley there. Go and see, and set it on fire." And Abishalom's servants set the field on fire. Then Joab's servants came to him with their clothes torn, and said, "Abishalom's servants have set the field on fire."
\v 31 And Joab rose, and came to Abishalom at his house, and said to him, "Why have your servants set my field on fire?"
\v 32 And Abishalom answered Joab, "Behold, I sent to you once and a second time, saying, 'Come here, that I may send you to the king, to say, "Why have I come from Geshur? It would be better for me to be still there. And now let me see the king's face, and if there is iniquity in me, let me be put to death."'"
\p
\v 33 And Joab came to the king and told him. And when he had called for Abishalom, he came to the king, and bowed himself to him and fell on his face to the ground before the king, and the king kissed Abishalom.
\c 15
\p
\v 1 And it happened after this, that Abishalom prepared for himself a chariot and horses, and fifty men to run before him.
\v 2 And Abishalom rose up early, and stood beside the way of the gate. And whenever there was any man who had a suit that should come to the king for judgment, then Abishalom called to him, and said, "What city are you from?" And he answered and said, "Your servant is from one of the tribes of Israel."
\v 3 And Abishalom said to him, "See, your matters are good and right, and there is no one from the king to hear you."
\v 4 And Abishalom said, "Who shall make me judge over the land, over Israel, that every man who has any suit might come to me, and I would do him justice?"
\v 5 And it happened that when any man came near to bow down to him, he put out his hand, and took hold of him, and kissed him.
\v 6 And Abishalom behaved like this to all Israel who came to the king for judgment. And Abishalom stole the hearts of all the men of Israel.
\p
\v 7 And it happened at the end of four years, that Abishalom said to the king, saying, "Please, let me go and pay my vow, which I have vowed to the \nd Lord\nd*, in Hebron.
\v 8 For your servant vowed a vow while I stayed at Geshur in Aram, saying, 'If the \nd Lord\nd* shall indeed bring me again to Jerusalem, then I will serve the \nd Lord\nd* in Hebron.'"
\v 9 And the king said to him, "Go in peace." And Abishalom arose, and went to Hebron.
\v 10 And Abishalom sent spies throughout all the tribes of Israel, saying, "As soon as you hear the sound of the trumpet, then you shall say, 'Abishalom is king in Hebron.'"
\p
\v 11 And two hundred men who were invited went with Abishalom out of Jerusalem. And they went in their simplicity, and they did not know anything.
\v 12 And Abishalom sent and called Ahithophel the Gilonite, David's counsellor, from his city, Giloh, while he was offering the sacrifices. And the conspiracy was going on and was strong, and the people went on increasing with Abishalom.
\p
\v 13 And a messenger came to David, saying, "The hearts of all Israel are with Abishalom."
\v 14 And David said to all his servants who were with him at Jerusalem, "Rise, and let us flee, otherwise none of us shall escape from Abishalom. Leave quickly, lest the people overtake us quickly, and bring down the city upon us, and strike the city with the edge of the sword."
\v 15 And the king's servants said to him, "Behold, we are your servants in whatever the king shall choose."
\v 16 And the king went out, and all his household with him. And the king left ten of his concubines to keep his house.
\p
\v 17 And the king went forth, and all the people with him, and they waited in Beth-merhak.
\v 18 And all his servants passed on beside him, and all the Cherethites and all the Pelethites, and they stopped beside a certain olive tree in the wilderness, and all the people passed on beside him. And all those who were with him, all the officers and the warriors, were 600 men, and they passed on beside him.
\p
And when all the Cherethites, all the Pelethites, and all the Gittites who had come to his feet from Gath, passed on,
\v 19 then the king said to Ittai the Gittite, "Why are you going with us too? Return, and stay with the king, for you are a foreigner, and an exile from your own place.
\v 20 Since you only came yesterday, should I today make you go up and down with us, seeing I go where I may? Go, return and take your brothers back, may the \nd Lord\nd* show mercy and truth to you."
\v 21 And Ittai answered the king, and said, "As the \nd Lord\nd* lives, and as you yourself live, my lord the king, surely in whatever place my lord the king shall be, whether for death or for life, even there also will your servant be."
\v 22 And David the king said to Ittai the Gittite, "Go and pass over with me." And Ittai passed over, and all his servants, and the king and all his men.
\v 23 And all the country blessed and wept with a loud voice, and all the people passed over. The king himself also passed over the brook Kidron, and all the people passed over before him on the Way of Olives in the wilderness.
\p
\v 24 And, behold, Zadok also \add passed over\add*, and all the Levites with him, bearing the ark of the covenant of God. And they set down the ark of the covenant until all the people had finished passing out of the city.
\v 25 And the king said to Zadok, "Carry the ark of God back into the city and set it in its place. If I find favor in the eyes of the \nd Lord\nd*, he will bring me again, and show me both it, and his dwelling place.
\v 26 And if he says to me thus, 'I have no delight in you,' behold, here I am, let him do to me as is good in his eyes."
\v 27 The king also said to Zadok the priest, "Behold, return into the city in peace, together with your two sons, Ahimaaz your son, and Jonathan the son of Abiathar.
\v 28 See, I will wait beside an olive tree in the wilderness, until there word comes from you to report to me."
\v 29 And Zadok and Abiathar carried the ark of God to Jerusalem again and set it there.
\p
\v 30 And David went up by the ascent of the Olives, and wept as he went up, and he had his head covered, and went barefoot. And of all the people who were with him every man covered his head, and they went up, weeping as they went up.
\v 31 And it was told to David, saying, "Ahithophel also is among the conspirators with Abishalom." And David said, "O \nd Lord\nd* God, please, turn the counsel of Ahithophel into foolishness."
\p
\v 32 And it happened that when David had come to the top, and worshipped the \nd Lord\nd* there, behold, David's friend Hushai the Archite came to meet him there with his coat torn, and earth on his head.
\v 33 And the king said to him, "If you pass on with me, then you will be a burden to me,
\v 34 and if you return to the city, and say to Abishalom, 'Your brothers departed, O king, after your father departed, and now I will be your servant, O king. Let me live. I have been your father's servant in time past, and I will now be your servant,'--- then defeat for me the counsel of Ahithophel.
\v 35 And Zadok and Abiathar will be the priests with you there. And it shall be, that whatever thing you hear from the king, you shall tell it to Zadok and Abiathar the priests.
\v 36 Behold, they have there with them their two sons, Ahimaaz, Zadok's son, and Jonathan, Abiathar's son, and by them you shall send to me everything that you shall hear."
\v 37 And Hushai the Archite, David's friend, came into the city, and Abishalom came into Jerusalem, and Ahithophel was with him.
\c 16
\p
\v 1 And when David was a little past the top, behold, Ziba the servant of Mephibaal met him, with a couple of donkeys saddled, and on them two hundred loaves of bread, an ephah of raisins, two hundred date-cakes, and a bottle of wine.
\v 2 And the king said to Ziba, "What do you mean by these?" And Ziba said, "The saddled donkeys are for the king's household to ride on, and the bread and date-cakes and raisins for the young men to eat, and the wine is so that whoever is faint in the wilderness may drink."
\v 3 And the king said, "Where is your master's son?" And Ziba said to the king, "Behold, he is staying in Jerusalem, and he said, 'Today the children of Israel will restore me the kingdom of my father.'"
\v 4 Then the king said to Ziba, "Behold, all that belongs to Mephibaal is yours." And Ziba said, "I bow down! I have found favour in your sight, my lord, O king."
\p
\v 5 And when king David came to Bahurim, behold, a man from the family of the house of Saul, whose name was Shimei the son of Gera, was coming out from there. He came out, cursing as he came,
\v 6 and throwing stones at David, and at all his servants. And all the people and all the mighty men were on the right hand and on the left of the king.
\v 7 And as he cursed, Shimei said, "Go away, go away, you man of blood, and man of belial\f + \fr 16:7 \ft "son of belial" or "daughter of belial" is a Hebrew idiom meaning 'worthless' or 'wicked'.\f*.
\v 8 The \nd Lord\nd* has returned on you all the blood of the house of Saul, in whose place you have reigned, and the \nd Lord\nd* has delivered the kingdom into the hand of Abishalom your son, and he caused you to see your own evil, because you are a man of blood."
\p
\v 9 Then Abishai the son of Zeruiah said to the king, "Why should this accursed dog curse my lord the king? Please let me go over and take off his head."
\v 10 And the king said to Abishai, "What do I have to do with you, O son of Zeruiah? And let him alone; for he curses me because the \nd Lord\nd* has said to him, 'Curse David;' and who shall say, 'Why have you done so?'"
\v 11 And David said to Abishai, and to all his servants, "Behold, my son who came forth from my body\f + \fr 16:11 \ft Hebrew: inward parts. The word is used to refer to either reproductive (as here) or digestive organs.\f* seeks my life: how much more this Benjamite now? Leave him alone and let him curse, for the \nd Lord\nd* has spoken to him.
\v 12 It may be that the \nd Lord\nd* will look on my affliction, and that the \nd Lord\nd* will return me good for his cursing of me this day."
\p
\v 13 And David and his men went by the way, and Shimei went along on the hill-side over against him, and cursed as he went, and threw stones at him, and threw dust.
\p
\v 14 And the king, and all the people who were with him, came weary at the Jordan, and he refreshed himself there.
\v 15 And Abishalom, and all the people, the men of Israel, came to Jerusalem, and Ahithophel was with him.
\v 16 And it happened, when Hushai the Archite, David's friend, had come to Abishalom, to the city, that Hushai said to Abishalom, "May the king live!
\v 17 And Abishalom said to Hushai, "Is this your kindness to your friend? Why didn't you go with your friend?"
\v 18 And Hushai said to Abishalom, "No! for I will belong to the one the \nd Lord\nd*, this people, and all the men of Israel have chosen, and I will stay with him.
\v 19 And again, who should I serve? Is it not in the presence of his son? As I have served your father, so will I be with you."
\p
\v 20 Then Abishalom said to Ahithophel, "Give your advice what we shall do."
\v 21 And Ahithophel said to Abishalom, "Go in to your father's concubines, who he has left to keep the house, and all Israel will hear that you have put your father to shame. Then your hands and the hands of all who are with you will be strong."
\v 22 And they spread Abishalom a tent on the top of the house and Abishalom went in to all his father's concubines in the sight of all Israel.
\v 23 And the advice of Ahithophel, which he gave in former days, was as if a man inquired at the oracle of God, so was all the advice of Ahithophel both with David and with Abishalom.
\c 17
\p
\v 1 And Ahithophel said to Abishalom, "Please let me choose for myself 10,000 men, and I will rise and pursue David tonight,
\v 2 and I will come upon him while he is weary and weak-handed, and I will make him afraid. And all the people who are with him will run away, and I will strike the king only.
\v 3 And all the people will come back to you, as a bride returns to her husband. It is only the life of one man that you seek, and all the people will be at peace."
\v 4 And the saying pleased Abishalom well, and all the elders of Israel.
\v 5 Then Abishalom said, "Please call Hushai the Archite also, and let us hear what he says."
\p
\v 6 And when Hushai had come to Abishalom, Abishalom spoke to Hushai about the word that Ahithophel had said. Shall we do his word? And if not, you speak."
\v 7 And Hushai said to Abishalom, "The advice that Ahithophel has given this time is not good."
\v 8 And Hushai said again, "You know your father and the men with him, that they are very mighty men, and they are bitter of soul, as a bear robbed of her cubs in the field. And your father is a man of war, and will not spend the night with the people.
\v 9 And behold, he will be hidden in some pit, or somewhere. And it will happen, when the people fall at the first attack, that whoever hears it will say, "There is a slaughter among the people who follow Abishalom."
\v 10 And even he who is valiant, whose heart is as the heart of a lion, will absolutely melt, for all Israel knows that your father is a mighty man, and those who are with him are valiant men.
\v 11 For this is the advice that I advise: Let all Israel be gathered together to you, from Dan even to Beer-sheba, like the sand that is by the sea in number, and that you go into their midst in your own person.
\v 12 And we shall come upon him in some place where he shall be found, and we will fall on him as the dew falls on the ground, and of him and of all the men who are with him we will not leave so much as one.
\v 13 And, if he has gone into a city, then all Israel shall bring ropes to that city, and we will draw it into the river, until there is not one small stone found there."
\p
\v 14 And Abishalom and all Israel said, "The advice of Hushai the Archite is better than the advice of Ahithophel." For the \nd Lord\nd* had commanded the defeat of the good counsel of Ahithophel, so that the \nd Lord\nd*'s evil might be brought on Abishalom.
\v 15 Then Hushai said to Zadok and to Abiathar the priests, "Ahithophel gave such and such advice to Abishalom and the elders of Israel, and I have given such and such advice.
\v 16 And now quickly tell the king, saying, 'Do not spend the night tonight at the fords of the wilderness, and also pass over the waters, lest the king and all the people who are with him be swallowed up.'"
\p
\v 17 And Jonathan and Ahimaaz were staying by En-rogel, and a maid-servant used to go and tell them, and they went and told king David. For they could not be seen or come into the city.
\v 18 And a young man saw them and told Abishalom, and both of them went away quickly and came to the house of a man in Bahurim, and the man had a well in his court, and they went down it.
\v 19 And the woman took the covering and spread it over the well's mouth and spread grain on it, and nothing was known.
\v 20 And Abishalom's servants came to the woman at the house and said, "Where are Ahimaaz and Jonathan?" And the woman said to them, "They have gone quickly over the water." And when they had looked and could not find them, they returned to Jerusalem.
\p
\v 21 And it happened, after they had gone, that they came up out of the well, and went and told king David. And they said to him, "Get up, and quickly cross the water, for Ahithophel has advised thus against you."
\v 22 Then David and all the people who were with him got up, and they passed over the Jordan. By the morning light not even one was left behind. Thus they crossed the Jordan.
\p
\v 23 And when Ahithophel saw that his advice was not followed, he saddled his donkey, and got up, and went home to his city, and set his house in order, and hanged himself. And he died, and was buried in the sepulchre of his father.
\p
\v 24 Then David came to Mahanaim. And Abishalom passed over the Jordan, he and all the men of Israel with him.
\v 25 And Abishalom set Amasa over the army instead of Joab. And Amasa was the son of a man whose name was Jether the Ishmaelite, who went in to Abigail the daughter of Jesse, sister to Zeruiah, Joab's mother.
\v 26 And Abishalom and all the men of Israel encamped in the land of Gilead.
\p
\v 27 And it happened, when David had come to Mahanaim, that Shobi the son of Nahash of Rabbah of the children of Ammon, and Machir the son of Ammiel of Lodebar, and Barzillai the Gileadite of Rogelim,
\v 28 brought ten beds, and rugs, and ten basins, and earthen vessels, and wheat, and barley, and meal, and parched grain, and beans, and lentils,
\v 29 and honey, and butter, and sheep, and cheese from the herd, and the brought them near for David and for his people to eat; for they said, "The people are hungry, and weary, and thirsty, in the wilderness."
\c 18
\p
\v 1 And David numbered all the people who were with him, and set captains of thousands and captains of hundreds over them.
\v 2 And David divided the people into three parts, one third under the hand of Joab, one third under the hand of Abishai the son of Zeruiah, Joab's brother, and one third under the hand of Ittai the Gittite. And the king said to the people, "I also will surely go forth with you myself."
\v 3 And the people said, "You shall not go forth, for if we run away no-one will set their heart on us, neither will anyone set their heart on us if half of us die. For you are like ten thousand of us. Therefore now it is better for us that you be ready to help us in the city."
\v 4 And the king said to them, "I will do what is good in your eyes." And the king stood beside the gate, and all the people went out by hundreds and by thousands.
\p
\v 5 And the king commanded Joab and Abishai and Ittai, saying, "Deal gently with the young man, with Abishalom, for my sake." And all the people heard when the king gave all the captains charge concerning Abishalom.
\v 6 And all the people went out into the field against Israel, and the battle was in the forest of Mahanaim.
\v 7 And the people of Israel were struck there before the servants of David, and there was a great slaughter of 20,000 men that day.
\v 8 For the battle was spread over the whole forest, and the forest consumed more people that day than the sword consumed.
\p
\v 9 And Abishalom was far ahead of the servants of David. And he was riding on his mule, and the mule went under the thick boughs of a great oak, and his head caught hold of the oak, and he was left hanging in the tree between heaven and earth, and the mule that was under him went on.
\v 10 And a certain man saw it, and told Joab, and said, "Behold, I saw Abishalom hanging in an oak."
\v 11 And Joab said to the man who had told him, "And, behold, you saw it, and why did you not strike him to the ground there? And I would have given you fifty of silver, and a girdle."
\v 12 And the man said to Joab, "Though I should receive a thousand of silver in my hand, I would still not put out my hand against the king's son, for the king charged you and Abishai and Ittai in our hearing saying, "Beware that no one touch the young man Abishalom."
\v 13 And how can I deal falsely against my soul? For no matter is hidden from the king, and you yourself have set yourself against \add me\add*."
\p
\v 14 Then Joab said, "Then I will begin before you." And Joab took three darts in his hand, and thrust them through the heart of Abishalom, while he was still alive in the midst of the oak.
\v 15 And ten young men who bore Joab's armour circled about and struck Abishalom, and killed him.
\v 16 And Joab blew the trumpet, and the people returned from pursuing Israel, for Joab held the people back.
\v 17 And Joab took Abishalom, and threw him into the great pit in the forest, and raised a very great heap of stones over him. And all Israel fled, every one to his tent.
\p
\v 18 And when he was still alive Abishalom had taken and raised up the pillar which is in the king's dale, for he said, "I have no son to keep my name in remembrance." And he called the pillar after his own name, and it is called Abishalom's monument to this day.
\p
\v 19 Then Ahimaaz the son of Zadok said to Joab, "Let me run now, let me bring news to David the king, for the \nd Lord\nd* has avenged him from the hand of his enemies."
\v 20 And Joab said, "You shall not be the one who brings news on this day, and you shall bring news another day. And today you shall bring no news, because the king's son is dead."
\v 21 Then said Joab to the Cushite, "Go and tell the king what you have seen." And the Cushite bowed to Joab, and ran.
\v 22 Then Ahimaaz the son of Zadok said yet again to Joab, "And come what may, please let me also run after the Cushite." And Joab said, "Why do you want to run, my son, seeing that you will have no reward for the news?"
\v 23 And Ahimaaz said, "And come what may, let me run." And he said to him, "Run." Then Ahimaaz ran by the way of the Plain, and outran the Cushite.
\p
\v 24 And David was sitting between the two gates, and the watchman went up to the roof of the gate to the wall, and lifted up his eyes, and looked, and, behold, a single man was running towards him.
\v 25 And the watchman called, and told the king. And the king said, "If he runs alone there is news in his mouth." And he came quickly and drew near.
\v 26 And the watchman saw another man running, and the watchman on the gate called and said, "Behold, another man running alone." And the king said, "He is also bringing news."
\v 27 And the watchman said, "I think the running of the first is like the running of Ahimaaz the son of Zadok." And the king said, "He is a good man, he comes with good news."
\p
\v 28 And Ahimaaz drew near, and said to the king, "All is well." And he bowed himself before the king with his face to the earth, and said, "Blessed be the \nd Lord\nd* your God, who has delivered up the men who lifted up their hand against my lord the king."
\v 29 And the king said, "Is the young man Abishalom alright?" And Ahimaaz answered, "When Joab the king's servant was sending your servant, I heard a great noise behind me, and I did not know what was there."
\v 30 And the king said, "Turn aside, and stand here." And he turned aside and stood behind him.
\p
\v 31 And, behold, the Cushite came, and he said to the king, "Tidings for my lord the king, for the \nd Lord\nd* has avenged you today of all those who rose up against you."
\v 32 And the king said to the Cushite, "Is it well with the young man Abishalom?" And the Cushite answered, "May the enemies of my lord the king, and all who rise up against you to harm you, be as that young man is."
\v 33 \f + \fr 18:33 \ft Some other editions count this verse (18:33) as 19:1 and number the verses numbered here as chapter 19 one verse number higher (i.e. 19:2 And they told Joab \... 19:3 And the victory that day \... etc.).\f*And the king began to weep, and went up to the chamber over the gate, and wept. And as he wept, he said thus, "O my son Abishalom, my son, my son Abishalom! Would that I had died for you, O Abishalom, my son, my son!"
\c 19
\p
\v 1 And they told Joab, "Behold, the king weeps and mourns for Abishalom."
\v 2 And the victory that day was turned into mourning for all the people, for the people heard it said that day, "The king is dismayed and grieves for his son."
\v 3 And the people came into the city stealthily that day, as people who are shattered and ashamed steal away when they run away in battle.
\v 4 And the king covered his face, and he cried with a loud voice, "O my son Abishalom, O Abishalom, my son!"
\p
\v 5 And Joab came into the house to the king, and said, "Today you have shamed the faces of your servants, who have saved your life today, and the lives of your sons and of your daughters, and the lives of your wives, and the lives of your concubines,
\v 6 because you love those who hate you, and hate those who love you. For you have declared this day, that princes and servants are nothing to you, for you know that if Abishalom were alive today, we would all have died; then you would have been well pleased.
\v 7 And now rise, go out and speak comfortably to your servants, for they have promised by the \nd Lord\nd* that if you do not go out there to meet with the people, not a man will stay with you this night. And know for yourself that will be worse to you than all the evil that has happened to you from your youth until now."
\p
\v 8 Then the king rose, and sat in the gate. And they told all the people, saying, "Behold, the king is sitting in the gate," and all the people came before the king.
\p
And every man of Israel had fled to his tent.
\v 9 And all the people were murmuring throughout all the tribes of Israel, saying, "David the king saved us from all our enemies, and he saved us out of the hand of the Philistines, and now he has fled out of the land and from being over the kingdom and from Abishalom.
\v 10 And Abishalom, who we anointed king over us, is dead in battle. And now, why don't you\sup ‡\sup* speak a word to bring the king back?
\p
And when the word of all Israel came to the king,
\v 11 then king David sent to Zadok and to Abiathar the priests, saying, "Speak to the elders of Judah, saying, 'Why are you the last to bring the king back to his house?
\v 12 You are my brothers, you are my bone and my flesh. Why then are you the last to bring the king back to his house?'
\v 13 And say to Amasa, 'Are you\sup †\sup* not my bone and my flesh? And now, God do so to me, and more also, if you are not captain of the army before me continually in place of Joab.'"
\v 14 And Amasa bowed the heart of all the men of Judah as one man and they sent to the king, "Return, you and all your servants."
\v 15 And the king returned, and came to the Jordan. And the men of Judah came to Gilgal, to go down to meet the king, to bring the king over the Jordan.
\p
\v 16 And Shimei the son of Gera, the Benjamite, who was from Bahurim, hurried and came down with the men of Judah to meet king David.
\v 17 And there were a thousand men of Benjamin with him, and Ziba the servant of the house of Saul, and his fifteen sons and his twenty servants with him, and they sent across the Jordan in the presence of the king.
\v 18 And they performed the service of bringing the king over, and doing what was good in his eyes.
\p
And Shimei the son of Gera fell on his face before the king, when he had come over the Jordan.
\v 19 And he said to the king, "Let my lord not impute iniquity, and do not remember that which your servant did perversely on the day that my lord the king went out of Jerusalem, that the king should take it to his heart.
\v 20 For your servant knows that I have sinned, and behold, I have come today as the first of all the house of Joseph to go down to meet my lord the king."
\p
\v 21 And Abishai the son of Zeruiah answered and said, "Shimei shall be put to death for this, because he cursed the \nd Lord\nd*'s anointed."
\v 22 And David said, "What do I have to do with you, you sons of Zeruiah, that you should be adversaries to me today? Shall any man be put to death today in Israel? For don't you know that today I am king over Israel?"
\v 23 And the king said to Shimei, "You shall not die." And the king promised to him.
\p
\v 24 And Mephibaal the son of Jonathan the son of Saul came down to meet the king, and he had neither dressed his feet nor his hands, nor trimmed his beard, nor washed his clothes, from the day the king departed until the day he came home in peace to Jerusalem.
\v 25 And it happened, when he had come from Jerusalem to meet the king, that the king said to him, "Why didn't you go with me, Mephibaal?"
\v 26 And Mephibaal said to him, "My lord, O king, my servant deceived me. For your servant said to him, "Saddle me a donkey, so I may ride on it, and go with the king," because your servant is lame.
\v 27 And he has slandered your servant to my lord the king, and my lord the king, as the angel of God, did what was good in my sight.
\v 28 For all my father's house were but dead men before my lord the king, yet you put your servant among those who ate at your own table. From whose hand could I receive justice?" And he cried out to the king.
\v 29 And the king said to him, "Why multiply your words? I say, you and Ziba divide the land."
\v 30 And Mephibaal said to the king, "Yes, let him take it all, for my lord the king has come in peace to his own house."
\p
\v 31 And Barzillai the Gileadite came down from Rogelim, and he went from the Jordan with the king, to conduct him from the Jordan.
\v 32 Now Barzillai was a very old man, even eighty years old, and he had provided the king with sustenance while he lay at Mahanaim, for he was a very great man.
\p
\v 33 And the king said to Barzillai, "Come over with me, and I will sustain your old age with me in Jerusalem."
\v 34 And Barzillai said to the king, "How many days would I live there, that I should go up with the king to Jerusalem?
\v 35 Today I am eighty years old. Can I discern between good and bad? Can your servant taste what I eat or what I drink? Can I hear the voice of singing men and singing women? Why then should your servant be a burden to my lord the king?
\v 36 For your servant would but just go over the Jordan with the king. And why should the king repay me with such a reward?
\v 37 Please let your servant turn back again, that I may die in my own city, and be buried in the grave of my father and my mother. And behold, your servant Chimham my son; let him go over with my lord the king, and do to him what is good in your eyes."
\p
\v 38 And the king said to him, "Chimham shall go over with me, and I will do to him that which is good in my eyes. And whatever you shall require of me I will do for you."
\v 39 And all the people went over the Jordan, and the king stayed, and the king kissed Barzillai, and blessed him. And Barzillai returned to his own place.
\v 40 And the king went over to Gilgal, and Chimham went over with him, and all the people of Judah and also half the people of Israel brought the king over.
\p
\v 41 And, behold, all the men of Israel came to the king, and said to the king, "Why have our brothers the men of Judah stolen you away, and brought the king, and his household, over the Jordan, and all David's men with him?"
\v 42 And the men of Judah answered the men of Israel and said, "Because the king is a close relative to us. Why then are you angry because of this? Have we eaten at all at the king's cost? Or has he given us any gift? Or has he brought us a present?"
\v 43 And the men of Israel answered the men of Judah, and said, "We have ten parts in the king, and also I am the firstborn rather than you. Why then did you despise us, that our advice should not be first had in bringing back our king?" And the words of the men of Judah were fiercer than the words of the men of Israel.
\c 20
\p
\v 1 And there happened to be there a worthless fellow, whose name was Sheba, the son of Bichri, a Benjamite. And he blew the trumpet, and said, "We have no portion in David, neither do we have any inheritance in the son of Jesse. Every man to his tents, O Israel."
\v 2 And all Israel went up from following David, and followed Sheba the son of Bichri. And the men of Judah clung to their king, from the Jordan as far as Jerusalem.
\p
\v 3 And David came to his house at Jerusalem, and the king took the ten women, his concubines who he had left to keep his house, and put them in a watch-house and sustained them, and he did not go into them. And they were shut up to the day of their death, living as widows.
\p
\v 4 Then said the king to Amasa, "Call the men of Judah together to me within three days, and you be here present.
\v 5 And Amasa went to call Judah together, and he delayed longer than the time which he had appointed him.
\v 6 And David said to Abishai, "Now Sheba the son of Bichri will do us more harm than Abishalom did. And now, take with you your lord's servants, and pursue after him, lest he should get fortified cities, and cast a shadow on our sight."
\v 7 And after Abishai he called out the people and Joab, and the Pelethites, and all the mighty men from Jerusalem to pursue after Sheba the son of Bichri.
\p
\v 8 When they were at the great stone which is on the hill, Amasa came to meet them. And Joab was girded in his tunic for clothing, and he was girded with a sword in its sheath fastened at his waist, and it came out and fell.
\v 9 And Joab said to Amasa, "Is it well with you, my brother?" And Joab took Amasa by the beard with his right hand to kiss him.
\v 10 And Amasa was not on guard against the sword that was in Joab's hand, and he struck him with it in the body, and spilled his bowels to the ground. And he did not strike him again, and he died. And Joab and Abishai his brother pursued after Sheba the son of Bichri.
\p
\v 11 And one of Joab's young men stood beside Amasa, and said, "He who favours Joab, and he who is for David, let him follow Joab."
\v 12 And Amasa lay wallowing in his blood in the middle of the highway. And when the man saw that all the people stood still, he carried Amasa out of the highway into the field, and threw a garment over him, when he saw that everyone who came by him stood still.
\v 13 When he had removed Amasa from the highway, all the people went on after Joab, to pursue after Sheba the son of Bichri.
\p
\v 14 And he went through all the tribes of Israel, even to Abel, and to Beth-maacah, and all the cities gathered together and also went after him.
\v 15 And they came and besieged him in Abel of Beth-maacah, and they cast up a mound against the city, and it stood against the rampart. And all the people who were with Joab were intending to topple the wall.
\p
\v 16 Then a wise woman cried out of the city, "Hear, hear! Please tell Joab to come here so I may speak with him.""
\v 17 And Joab came near her, and the woman said, "Are you Joab?" And he answered, "I am." Then she said, "Hear the words of your handmaid." And he answered, "I hear. Speak."
\v 18 Then she said, "They used to say a saying in the old time, "They shall surely ask at Abel and Dan, whether what the builders of Israel intended has been carried out."
\v 19 You seek to destroy a city and a mother in Israel. Why will you swallow up the inheritance of the \nd Lord\nd*?"
\v 20 And Joab answered and said, "Far be it from me, that I should swallow up or destroy.
\v 21 The matter is not so. For a man of the hill-country of Ephraim, Sheba the son of Bichri, has lifted up his hand against the king, even against David. Deliver him only, and I will leave the city." And the woman said to Joab, "Behold, his head shall be thrown to you from the wall."
\v 22 And she spoke wisely to all the city. And they cut off the head of Sheba the son of Bichri, and threw it out to Joab. And Joab blew the trumpet, and they were dispersed from the city, every man to his tent. And Joab returned to Jerusalem to the king.
\p
\v 23 And Joab was over all the host of Israel, and Benaiah the son of Jehoiada was over the Cherethites and over the Pelethites,
\v 24 and Adonairam was over the forced labour, and Jehoshaphat the son of Ahilud was recorder,
\v 25 and Shavsha was scribe, and Zadok and Abiathar were priests,
\v 26 and also Jehoiada the Jairite was chief minister to David.
\c 21
\p
\v 1 And there was a famine in the land in the days of David three years, year after year, and David sought the face of the \nd Lord\nd*. And the \nd Lord\nd* said, "There is blood on Saul and on his house. The guilt is because of his killing of the Gibeonites."
\v 2 And the king called the Gibeonites, and spoke to them. (And the Gibeonites were not of the children of Israel, for they were of the remnant of the Amorites, and the children of Israel had promised them not to destroy them. And Saul had risen to exterminate them in zeal for Israel and Judah).
\p
\v 3 And David said to the Gibeonites, "What shall I do for you? and how shall I make atonement, that you may bless the inheritance of the \nd Lord\nd*?"
\v 4 And the Gibeonites said to him, "It is no matter of silver or gold between us and Saul, or his house, neither is it for us to put any man to death from all Israel." And he said, "What do you want? For I will do it for you."
\v 5 And they said to the king, "The man who set himself against us and persecuted us, and that plotted against us, \add that\add* we should be destroyed from remaining in any of the borders of Israel,
\v 6 let seven men of his sons be delivered to us, and we will hang them up to the \nd Lord\nd* in Gibeah of Saul, the chosen of the \nd Lord\nd*." And the king said, "I will give them to you."
\p
\v 7 And the king spared Mephibaal, the son of Jonathan the son of Saul, because of the \nd Lord\nd*'s oath that they had sworn between them, between David and Jonathan the son of Saul.
\v 8 And the king took the two sons of Rizpah the daughter of Aiah, who she bore to Saul, Armoni and Mephibaal, and the five sons of Merab the daughter of Saul, who she bore to Adriel the son of Barzillai the Meholathite.
\v 9 And he delivered them into the hands of the Gibeonites, and they hanged them in the mountain before the \nd Lord\nd*, and the seven fell there together. And they were put to death in the days of Ziv, at the beginning of barley harvest.
\p
\v 10 And Rizpah the daughter of Aiah the concubine of Saul took sackcloth, and spread it for her upon the rock, from the beginning of harvest until the water of God poured from heaven. And she did not allow the birds of the heavens to rest on them by day, nor the beasts of the field by night.
\v 11 And it was told David all that Rizpah the daughter of Aiah, the concubine of Saul, had done.
\v 12 And David went and took the bones of Saul and the bones of Jonathan his son from the men of Jabesh-gilead, who had stolen them from the street of Beth-shan, where the Philistines had hanged them, in the day that the Philistines slew Saul in Gilboa.
\v 13 And he brought the bones of Saul and the bones of Jonathan his son up from there, and they gathered the bones of those who were hanged,
\v 14 and they buried the bones of Saul and Jonathan and the bones of those who were hanged in the country of Benjamin in Zela, in the sepulchre of Kish his father. And they performed all that the king commanded. And after that God atoned for the land.
\p
\v 15 And the Philistines had war again with Israel, and David went down with his men and fought against the Philistines. And David grew faint,
\v 16 and Dado the son of Joash, who was of the sons of the giant captured him; the weight of his spear was 300 shekels of brass in weight, he being clothed with armour, thought he would kill David.
\v 17 And Abishai the son of Zeruiah saved David, and struck the Philistine, and killed him. Then the men of David promised, saying, "You shall not go out to battle with us any more, that you should not extinguish the lamp of Israel."
\p
\v 18 And it happened after this, that there was again war with the Philistines at Gezer. Then Sibbecai the Hushathite killed Sippai, who was of the sons of the giant.
\v 19 And there was again war with the Philistines at Gob, and Elhanan the son of Jaar killed Lahmi the brother of Goliath the Gittite, the staff of whose spear was like a weaver's beam.
\v 20 And there was again war at Gath with the Philistines, where there was a man of great stature, who had six fingers on every hand, and six toes on every foot, twenty four in number, and he also was born to the giant.
\v 21 And when he defied Israel, Jonathan the son of Shimeah, David's brother, killed him.
\v 22 These four were born to the giant in Gath, and they fell by the hand of David, and by the hand of his servants.
\c 22
\p
\v 1 And David spoke to the \nd Lord\nd* the words of this song in the day that the \nd Lord\nd* delivered him out of the hand of all his enemies, and out of the hand of Sheol.
\v 2 And he said,"I have compassion on you."
\p
O \nd Lord\nd*, my strength,
\p
The \nd Lord\nd* is my rock, and my fortress, and my deliverer, even mine;
\p
\v 3 My God, my rock, in him will I take refuge;
\p
My shield, and the horn of my salvation, my high tower, and my refuge;
\p
My saviour, he saves me from violent men, who is worthy to be praised.
\p
\v 4 I will call upon the \nd Lord\nd*,
\p
So shall I be saved from my enemies.
\p
\v 5 For the cords of death were around me;
\p
The floods of ungodliness made me afraid.
\p
\v 6 The cords of Sheol were around me;
\p
The snares of death came upon me.
\p
\v 7 In my distress I called upon the \nd Lord\nd*;
\p
Yes, I cried to my God:
\p
And he heard my voice out of his temple,
\p
And my cry \add came\add* into his ears.
\p
\v 8 Then the earth shook and trembled,
\p
The foundations of heaven quaked and were shaken, because he was angry.
\p
\v 9 Smoke went up out of his nostrils,
\p
And fire out of his mouth devoured: coals were kindled by it.
\p
\v 10 He bowed the heavens also, and came down;
\p
And thick darkness was under his feet.
\p
\v 11 And he rode on a cherub, and he did fly;
\p
Yes, he sped on the wings of the wind.
\p
\v 12 And he made darkness his hiding place,
\p
Canopies around him, darkness of waters, thick clouds of the skies.
\p
\v 13 At the brightness before him passed hailstones and coals of fire.
\p
\v 14 The \nd Lord\nd* thundered from heaven,
\p
And the Most High uttered his voice.
\p
\v 15 And he sent out arrows, and scattered them;
\p
Lightnings, and discomfited them.
\p
\v 16 Then the channels of the sea appeared,
\p
The foundations of the world were laid bare,
\p
By the rebuke of the \nd Lord\nd*,
\p
At the blast of his nostrils.
\p
\v 17 He sent from on high, he took me;
\p
He drew me out of many waters;
\p
\v 18 He delivered me from my enemies of strength,
\p
From those who hated me; for they were too mighty for me.
\p
\v 19 They came upon me in the day of my calamity;
\p
And the \nd Lord\nd* was my stay.
\p
\v 20 He also brought me forth into a large place;
\p
He delivered me, because he delighted in me.
\p
\v 21 The \nd Lord\nd* rewarded me according to my righteousness;
\p
According to the cleanness of my hands he has recompensed me.
\p
\v 22 For I have kept the ways of the \nd Lord\nd*,
\p
And have not wickedly departed from my God.
\p
\v 23 For all his ordinances were before me;
\p
And I did not put away his statutes from me.
\p
\v 24 I was also blameless with him;
\p
And I kept myself from my iniquity.
\p
\v 25 And the \nd Lord\nd* has recompensed me according to my righteousness,
\p
According to the cleanness of my hands in his eyes.
\p
\v 26 With the merciful you will show yourself merciful;
\p
With the perfect man you will show yourself perfect;
\p
\v 27 With the pure you will show yourself pure;
\p
And with the perverse you will show yourself astute.
\p
\v 28 For you will save the afflicted people;
\p
And you bring down haughty eyes.
\p
\v 29 For you light my lamp, O \nd Lord\nd*;
\p
And the \nd Lord\nd* my God will lighten my darkness.
\p
\v 30 For by you I run upon a troop;
\p
By my God I leap over a wall.
\p
\v 31 As for God, his way is perfect:
\p
The word of the \nd Lord\nd* is tried;
\p
He is a shield to all those who take refuge in him.
\p
\v 32 For who is God, but the \nd Lord\nd*?
\p
And who is a rock, but our God?
\p
\v 33 The God who girds me with strength,
\p
And sets my way blameless,
\p
\v 34 He makes my feet like those of hinds,
\p
And sets me upon my high places.
\p
\v 35 He teaches my hands to war,
\p
So that my arms bend a bow of brass.
\p
\v 36 You have also given me the shield of your salvation;
\p
And your right hand upholds me,
\p
And your condescension makes me great.
\p
\v 37 You have enlarged my steps under me;
\p
And my feet have not slipped.
\p
\v 38 I have pursued my enemies, and destroyed them;
\p
Neither did I turn again until they were consumed.
\p
\v 39 And I shattered them through, and they cannot arise:
\p
Yes, they have fallen under my feet.
\p
\v 40 For you have girded me with strength for the battle;
\p
You have subdued under me those who rose up against me.
\p
\v 41 And my enemies, you have given me their neck,
\p
That I might cut off those who hate me.
\p
\v 42 They cried for help, and there was none to save;
\p
Even to the \nd Lord\nd*, and he did not answered them.
\p
\v 43 Then I beat them small as the dust before the wind;
\p
I emptied them out as the mire of the streets.
\p
\v 44 You have also delivered me from the strivings of the people;
\p
You have placed me to be the head of the nations:
\p
A people who I have not known shall serve me.
\p
\v 45 The foreigners shall submit themselves to me:
\p
As soon as they hear of me, they shall obey me.
\p
\v 46 The foreigners shall fade away,
\p
And shall come trembling out of their close places.
\p
\v 47 The \nd Lord\nd* lives; and blessed be my rock;
\p
And exalted be God, the rock of my salvation,
\p
\v 48 Even the God who executes vengeance for me,
\p
And who subdues peoples under me,
\p
\v 49 And who brings me forth from my enemies:
\p
Yes, you lift me up above those who rise up against me;
\p
You deliver me from the violent man.
\p
\v 50 Therefore I will give thanks to you among the nations, O \nd Lord\nd*,
\p
And will sing praises to your name.
\p
\v 51 He gives great deliverance to his king,
\p
And shows mercy to his anointed,
\p
To David and to his seed, for evermore.
\c 23
\p
\v 1 And these are the last words of David.
\p
David the son of Jesse says,
\p
And the man who God established says,
\p
The anointed of the God of Jacob,
\p
And the sweet psalmist of Israel:
\p
\v 2 The Spirit of the \nd Lord\nd* spoke by me,
\p
And his word was upon my tongue.
\p
\v 3 The God of Jacob said,
\p
The Rock of Israel spoke by me:
\p
One who rules over men righteously,
\p
Who rules in the fear of God,
\p
\v 4 \add He shall be\add* as the light of the morning, when the sun rises,
\p
A morning without clouds,
\p
\add When\add* the tender grass \add springs\add* out of the earth,
\p
Through clear shining after rain.
\p
\v 5 For is not my house so with God?
\p
For he has made an everlasting covenant
\p
To save me, until now, in all things; And he will keep it:
\p
For all those that are set against me he will not desire,
\p
For all those that grow like a thorn.
\p
\v 6 And those of belial\f + \fr 23:6 \ft "son of belial" or "daughter of belial" is a Hebrew idiom meaning 'worthless' or 'wicked'.\f* are, all of them, as a thorn of a fire,
\p
Because they cannot be taken with the hand;
\p
\v 7 Nor can a man touch them,
\p
Except with iron or wood:
\p
And burning,they shall be utterly burned with fire in their shame.
\p
\v 8 These are the names of the mighty men David had: Jeshbaal the son of a Hachmonite, chief of the three; he lifted up his spear against 900 killed at one time.
\v 9 And after him was Eleazar the son of Dodai, one of the three mighty men. He was with David at Pasdammim when the Philistines were gathered together there to battle, and the men of Israel went up to meet them.
\v 10 He rose, and struck the Philistines until his hand was weary, and his hand stuck to the sword. And the \nd Lord\nd* worked a great salvation that day, and the people returned after him only to take spoil.
\v 11 And after him was Shammah the son of Agee a Hararite. And the Philistines were gathered together at Lehi, where there was a plot of ground full of lentils, and the people fled from the Philistines.
\v 12 And he stood in the middle of the plot, and defended it, and killed the Philistines. And the \nd Lord\nd* worked a great salvation that day.
\p
\v 13 And three of the thirty chief men went down, and came to the rock to David at the cave of Adullam, and the troop of the Philistines was encamped in the valley of Rephaim.
\v 14 And David was in the stronghold then, and the garrison of the Philistines was in Bethlehem then.
\v 15 And David longed, and said, "Oh that someone would give me water to drink of the well of Bethlehem, which is by the gate!"
\v 16 And the three mighty men broke through the host of the Philistines, and drew water out of the well of Bethlehem, that was by the gate, and took it, and brought it to David. And David would not drink of it, and poured it out to the \nd Lord\nd*.
\v 17 And he said, "Far be it from me before the \nd Lord\nd*, that I should do this! Shall I drink the blood of the men who went with their souls?" And he would not drink it. These things the three mighty men did.
\p
\v 18 And Abishai, the brother of Joab, the son of Zeruiah, was chief of the thirty. And he lifted up his spear against three hundred and killed them, and had a name among the three.
\v 19 By the three he was honoured like two men, and he was made their captain; and he did not attain to the three.
\p
\v 20 And Benaiah the son of Jehoiada, the son of a valiant man of Kabzeel, who had done mighty deeds, he killed the two sons of Ariel of Moab. He also went down and killed a lion in the middle of a pit in time of snow.
\v 21 And he killed an Egyptian, a man of appearance. And the Egyptian had a spear in his hand, and he went down to him with a staff, and plucked the spear out of the Egyptian's hand, and killed him with his own spear.
\v 22 These things Benaiah the son of Jehoiada did, and had a name among the three mighty men.
\v 23 By the three he was honoured, and he did not attain to the three. And David set him over his guard.
\p
And these are the names of the mighty men of king David:
\v 24 Asahel the brother of Joab was one of the thirty, Elhanan the son of Dodo of Bethlehem,
\v 25 Shammah the Harodite, Elika the Harodite,
\v 26 Helez the Pelonite, Ira the son of Ikkesh the Tekoite,
\v 27 Abiezer the Anathothite, Sibbecai the Hushathite,
\v 28 Zalmon the Ahohite, Maharai the Netophathite,
\v 29 Heldai the son of Baanah the Netophathite, Ittai the son of Ribbai of Gibeah of the children of Benjamin,
\v 30 Benaiah a Pirathonite, Hurai of the brooks of Gaash,
\v 31 Abiel the Arbathite, Azmaveth the Bahurumite,
\v 32 Eliahba the Shaalbonite, Jashen the Gunite, Jonathan the son of
\v 33 Shammah the Hararite, Ahiam the son of Sachar the Hararite,
\v 34 Eliphelet the son of Ahasbai the Mecherathite, Eliam the son of Ahithophel the Gilonite,
\v 35 Hezro the Carmelite, Paarai the Arbite,
\v 36 Joel the brother of Nathan of Zobah, Mibhar the son of Hagri,
\v 37 Zelek the Ammonite, Naharai the Beerothite, the armour-bearer to Joab the son of Zeruiah,
\v 38 Ira the Ithrite, Gareb the Ithrite,
\v 39 Uriah the Hittite: thirty seven in all.
\c 24
\p
\v 1 And the anger of God was kindled against Israel again, and he moved David against them, saying, "Go, number Israel and Judah."
\v 2 And the king said to Joab and to the captains of the host who were with him in Jerusalem, "Go about now through all Israel and Judah, from Dan even to Beer-sheba, and number the people, and bring it to me that I may know the sum of the people."
\v 3 And Joab said to the king, "And may the \nd Lord\nd* your God add to the people, however many they may be, a hundredfold, and may the eyes of my lord the king see it! And why does my lord the king delight in this thing?"
\v 4 Nevertheless, the king's word defeated Joab and the captains of the host. And Joab and the captains of the host went out from the presence of the king, to number the people of Israel.
\p
\v 5 And they passed over the Jordan, and began from Aroer, and from the city that is in the middle of the valley of Gad, and to Jazer.
\v 6 Then they came to Gilead, and to Kadesh of the Hittites, and they came to Dan, and they went around Sidon,
\v 7 and came to the stronghold of Tyre, and to all the cities of the Hivites, and of the Canaanites, and they went out to the south of Judah, at Beer-sheba.
\v 8 And when they had gone about through all the land, they came to Jerusalem at the end of nine months and twenty days.
\v 9 And Joab gave up the sum of the numbering of the people to the king. And there were in Israel 900,000 men who drew the sword, and the men of Judah were 400,000 men who drew the sword.
\p
\v 10 And David's heart struck him after he had numbered the people. And David said to the \nd Lord\nd*, "I have sinned greatly in this thing that I have done. And now, O \nd Lord\nd*, please put away the iniquity of your servant, for I have done very foolishly."
\v 11 And when David rose up in the morning, the word of the \nd Lord\nd* came to Gad, David's seer, saying,
\v 12 "Go and speak to David, 'Thus says the \nd Lord\nd*, "I offer you three things, choose one of them, that I may do it to you."'"
\v 13 And Gad came to David, and told him, and said to him, "Choose for yourself: shall three years of famine come to you in your land, or will you run away from your enemies for three months while they pursue you, or shall there be three days' pestilence in the land? And now consider and see what answer I shall return to him who sent me."
\v 14 And David said to Gad, "I am in great distress! Only now let me fall into the hand of the \nd Lord\nd*, for his mercies are great, and do not let me fall into the hand of man."
\p
And David chose the pestilence, and in the days of the wheat harvest,
\v 15 the \nd Lord\nd* gave a pestilence on Israel from the morning even to the time of nourishment. And the plague caused sickness among the people, and 70,000 men of the people died from Dan even to Beer-sheba.
\v 16 And when the angel stretched out his hand toward Jerusalem to destroy it, the \nd Lord\nd* repented of the evil, and said to the angel who destroyed the people, "It is enough. Now hold back your hand." And the angel of the \nd Lord\nd* was by the threshing-floor of Araunah the Jebusite.
\p
And David lifted up his eyes, and saw the angel of the \nd Lord\nd* standing between earth and heaven, with a drawn sword in his hand stretched out over Jerusalem. And David and the elders, covered in sackcloth, fell on their faces.
\v 17 And David spoke to the \nd Lord\nd* when he saw the angel who struck the people, and said, "Behold, it is I who have sinned. And it is I, the shepherd, who have done wrong. And these sheep, what have they done? Please let your hand be against me and against my father's house."
\p
\v 18 And Gad came to David that day, and said, "Go up, raise an altar to the \nd Lord\nd* in the threshing-floor of Araunah the Jebusite."
\v 19 And David went up as Gad had said, as the \nd Lord\nd* commanded.
\v 20 And Araunah looked out, and saw the king and his servants approaching him, and Araunah went out and bowed himself before the king with his face to the ground.
\v 21 And Araunah said, "Why has my lord the king come to his servant?" And David said to him, "To buy the threshing-floor from you, to build an altar to the \nd Lord\nd*, that the plague may be stopped from the people."
\v 22 And Araunah said to David, "Let my lord the king take and offer up what is good in his eyes. Behold, the oxen for the burnt-offering, and the threshing instruments and the yokes of the oxen for the wood.
\v 23 All this, O king, Araunah gives to the king." And Araunah said to the king, "May the \nd Lord\nd* your God accept you."
\v 24 And the king said to Araunah, "No, for I will surely buy it from you at a price. Neither will I offer burnt-offerings to the \nd Lord\nd* my God which cost me nothing." And David bought the threshing-floor and the oxen for fifty shekels of silver.
\p
\v 25 And David built an altar to the \nd Lord\nd* there, and offered burnt-offerings and peace-offerings. And Solomon added to the altar later, for it was small at first. And the \nd Lord\nd* was entreated for the land, and the plague was stayed from Israel.
